<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Offer Fresh Contribution to Chernobyl's Shut-down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission today
announced that it will contribute another 100 million ECU (113
million U.S. dollars) to the final shut-down of the Chernobyl
nuclear power plant in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
The donation, committed by the executive body of the 15-nation
European Union, doubles the amount it has contributed to Chernobyl.
</P>
<P>
EU's foreign affairs commissioner Hans van den Broek said that
the EU has offered a substantial contribution to make the damaged
Unit 4 reactor safe in Chernobyl.
</P>
<P>
"We now urge the rest of the international community to do its
share," said van den Broek, who said that a permanent closure of
the Chernobyl plant by the year 2000 remains the final target of
the commission.
</P>
<P>
The latest EU contribution followed a decision made the
Group-of-Seven industrial nations in Denver, United States, last
June to finance 261.6 million ECU (300 million dollars) to make
the reactor safe. The total need is estimated at 654 million ECU
(750 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
