<HEADLINE> B-52 Bombers Leave for Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Three U.S. B-52 bombers
took off from its Louisiana air base on Thursday to their
destination, the island of Diego Garcia in the Indian Ocean. and
the other three will follow soon.
</P>
<P>
The B-52 bombers and six F-117a stealth fighters, which
departed for Kuwait on Wednesday, were ordered by President Bill
Clinton to reinforce the American air and naval force already
poised near Iraq in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
These warplanes, plus those on board the aircraft carrier
George Washington expected to arrive in the Gulf this weekend,
will make a total of 300 U.S. planes and 22 ships in the region.
</P>
<P>
Clinton never ruled out a military option to force Iraq
President Saddam Hussein to reverse course in his decision to
expel American weapons inspectors, although he said he wanted to
settle the weapons inspection dispute with Iraq peacefully.
</P>
</TEXT>
