<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Deficit Surges to $11.1 Billion in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. trade deficit
soared 17 percent in September as imports from Asia helped widen
the trade gap, the Commerce Department said here today.
</P>
<P>
A report released by the department said the deficit in
September was 11.1 billion U.S. dollars, the worst since January.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. imports rose 1.2 percent to a new record of 89.1
billion dollars in September, while exports slipped by 0.7 percent
to 78 billion.
</P>
<P>
The deficit with Japan rose 6.9 percent to 5.1 billion dollars,
as U.S. purchases of electrical machinery and photo equipment from
Japan rose while sales of aircraft and cars to Japan slumped.
</P>
<P>
Deficit with its two neighboring partners also increased. The
gap with Canada, the biggest U.S. trade partner, edged up 0.3
percent to 1.3 billion dollars while the imbalance with Mexico
jumped 32.4 percent, also to 1.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
On a year-on-year basis, the deficit for the first nine months
is equivalent to 115.3 billion dollars, surpassing the eight-year
high of 111 billion dollars recorded in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts predicted the deficit will rise to 200 billion
dollars next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Debts Reduce Confidence Among Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The debt situation in many
African countries has led to a significant loss in confidence
among foreign investors, an African Development Bank (ADB)
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Visiting ADB's Risk Management Unit chief Tim Turner said in
an interview with the Zimbabwe News Agency that the situation in
the past few years had become worse as it reduced most African
countries to dependents of the west.
</P>
<P>
"Debt is not really a problem, but the big problem lies with
certain financial institutions which dictate to countries what
the money borrowed should be used for," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said countries had their own priorities and should be given
the chance to fulfill them before money lenders intervene to
dictate what best suits them.
</P>
<P>
Although Turner admitted that the ADB was being influenced on
some of its policies by the International Monetary Fund and the
World Bank, he said the bank would strive to maintain its
"Africanness".
</P>
<P>
"We want to help different sections of economies in Africa, no
matter how big or small they are. We will support any measures
that increase private sector participation and other measures
that instill financial discipline," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
ADB this year committed 2.6 billion Zimbabwe Dollars (180
million U.S. Dollars) for social and economic projects to
Zimbabwe in recognition of the country's efforts to bring
financial discipline in its economy as well as taking measures to
address its economic woes during the next phase of its reform
program, Turner said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
