<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Queen Elizabeth Pledges to Listen to People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Queen Elizabeth and Prince
Philip on Thursday celebrated their golden wedding anniversary
with a promise to listen to the people.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a government banquet on the anniversary of her
golden wedding, the queen said the monarchy existed only "with the
people's support and consent."
</P>
<P>
"The message to a Royal family is sometimes obscured by
deference, rhetoric or the conflicting currents of public
opinion," she said.
</P>
<P>
The luncheon for 300 guests was staged at the Banqueting Hall
where Charles I was executed in 1649.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the host and Prime Minister Tony Blair, four former
British prime ministers, seven kings, 10 queens, a grand duke, 26
princes and 27 princesses were also present at the grand banquet
after attending a ceremony at the Westminster Abbey for the
biggest regal gathering since Elizabeth's coronation in 1953.
</P>
<P>
She was greeted at the entrance to the abbey by a fanfare of
trumpets and then the congregation joined in "Praise My Soul The
King of Heaven", one of her favorite hymns that was played at
their wedding.
</P>
<P>
The Royal family's popularity, already shaky following a decade
of scandal and marital breakdown among the younger royals,
plummeted following the death of the publicly-adored Princess
Diana at the end of August.
</P>
<P>
Since then, royal officials have made clear that ways of
modernizing the 1,000-year-old monarchy are under consideration.
But a poll released on the eve of the anniversary showed that
there is far to go.
</P>
<P>
Only one in five young people considered the monarchy
important, while overall backing for the royals had plunged from
65 percent in 1983 to 32 percent today.
</P>
<P>
"Young people are certainly less in awe of traditional British
institutions," the annual British Social Attitudes survey
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK PM Praises Queen at Golden Wedding Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair praised Queen Elizabeth today for being "unstuffy, unfussy
and unfazed by anything".
</P>
<P>
At a "People's Banquet" to celebrate the 50th wedding
anniversary of the queen and Prince Philip, Blair said the Royal
family had steered "through the terrible test" of Princess Diana's
death in a car crash on August 31.
</P>
<P>
After Diana's death, the 1,000-year-old monarchy was criticized
for not immediately joining in the spontaneous national outpouring
of grief. But Blair stoutly defended the Royal family.
</P>
<P>
Blair told the queen: "You are our queen. We respect and
cherish you. You are simply the best of British."
</P>
<P>
"I know from the conversations we had during those days how
deeply you felt those events for yourself, Prince Charles and the
boys," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I know too, contrary to some of the hurtful things that were
said at the time, how moved you were by the outpouring of grief
which followed as, in the security of your own home, you sought as
a family to help the boys."
</P>
<P>
Present at the banquet held at the Banqueting Hall were 300
guests, including the four former British prime ministers, seven
kings, 10 queens 26 princes and 27 princesses from around the
world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
