<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Secretary-General: Diplomacy Works </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Encouraged by Iraq's
decision to allow U.N. arms inspectors to resume work in the
country on Friday, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said today
that the new development is a proof of diplomacy's role.
</P>
<P>
"It proves that diplomacy sometimes works and you don't always
have to fight to win," Annan told reporters when entering the U.N.
headquarters this morning.
</P>
<P>
Iraq on Thursday announced that it agreed to allow U.S. arms
inspectors back into the country, ending three weeks of defiance
of U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The announcement followed a ministerial meeting in Geneva by
foreign ministers of France, Britain, Russia and the U.S. and the
representative of China. The participants urged Iraq to
unconditionally accept the return of the U.N. inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he hopes that all inspectors will be back in Iraq by
Friday since they are only an hour or so from Baghdad. Iraq
ordered out the Americans in the inspection teams last Thursday
while chief U.N. inspector Richard Butler pulled out all inspectors
who are currently staying in Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
The United States has increased its military presence in the
Gulf area while seeking diplomatic solutions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council Special Commission on Iraq will hold
an emergency meeting Friday to discuss the latest developments.
</P>
<P>
Asked if it is time to review the question of the whole
sanctions regime against Iraq, Annan said it is part of the
current discussions.
</P>
<P>
"There has been indications that we will look at it," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I think that the food-for-oil can be strengthened and can work
better," he said, adding "we are determined to make it work."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
