<HEADLINE> Butler Expects U.N. Inspectors Return to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Chief U.N. weapons
inspector Richard Butler on Thursday expected the return of
inspectors including Americans to Baghdad on Friday following
Iraq's permission.
</P>
<P>
"At first light tomorrow we'll be off and back to Baghdad
provided that what we've heard on the wire services is right, that
Iraq really has decided this..." Butler told ABC's Good Morning
America in an interview.
</P>
<P>
Iraq earlier made a statement that it decided to allow U.N.
weapons inspectors including Americans back to Baghdad and resume
their work.
</P>
<P>
"We won't be able to fly this afternoon because when it gets
dark it's best not to operate our aircraft under those
conditions," Butler said.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 U.N. inspectors left Baghdad last Friday after
Iraq expelled six American inspectors, accused of spying for the
United States under the guise of U.N. weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
"We'll be on the plane tomorrow and back in business on
Friday," Butler said. 
