<HEADLINE> World Gold Demand Reaches Record Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- World demand for gold in the
first nine months of this year reached record levels despite of
the recent currency and stock markets turmoil in some big Asian
markets, Financial Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Citing figures from the World Gold Council (WGC), the newspaper
said that gold demand in the first nine months of 1997 was at
2,191 tons, 11 percent up over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, gold demand in the fourth quarter also started
strongly and the manager of gold market analysis of WGC George
Milling-Stanley was quoted as saying that "there is a very good
chance it (1997) will be a record year".
</P>
<P>
The WGC, which is funded by gold producers and monitors markets
accounting for 80 percent of total demand, said that india, the
largest gold consuming nation, was the driving force behind the
record.
</P>
<P>
Indian gold demand in the nine months amounted to 535 tons,
44 percent up and ahead of the 508 tons for all of last year.
</P>
<P>
The WGC dismissed the idea that gold demand was being driven to
record levels entirely by low prices, saying that the strength of
the US dollar, which is used for the international price of gold,
had made the metal seem much more expensive in some countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
