<HEADLINE> U.S. Banks Suffer Losses in Latin America, Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Major U.S. banks lost up to
400 million U.S. dollars trading in volatile Latin American and
Russian emerging markets in October.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the USA Today, Most of the damage was
inflicted on Chase Manhattan, the nation's largest bank.
</P>
<P>
It acknowledges pretax losses of 160 million last month,
stemming mostly from declines in the value of emerging-market debt
and Euro-bonds it held or sold, the paper said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The only other bank to publicly announce trading losses for
October is BankBoston, which had a loss of 20 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The majority of other aggressive emerging-market players --
such as commercial banks J.P. Morgan and Citibank, and investment
houses Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley -- say losses were not
material to overall earnings.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that losses, expected to be included in
fourth-quarter earnings reports, are far less than feared from
last month's dust-up when many emerging markets suddenly crashed
almost 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Those markets have recovered somewhat in recent weeks, but
volatility is expected to remain, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Some traders say the heaviest losses may have been absorbed
by European banks, some of whom are aggressive players in Latin
America and Eastern Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
