<HEADLINE> Britain not to Seek Police Probe on Patten Book </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The British government would
not seek an investigation into whether revelations in a biograph
about the last Hong Kong governor breached Britain's Official
Secrets Act, a minister said today.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General John Morris said in a written answer to a
parliamentary question that he had decided to rule out a police
probe after being influenced by "intelligence and foreign
relations considerations".
</P>
<P>
"I concluded that intelligence and foreign relations
considerations outweighed other public interest considerations
which might otherwise have required a prosecution in respect of
any offence established by a criminal investigation," Morris said.
</P>
<P>
"It followed that no useful purpose would have been served for
there to have been a police investigation in this matter," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The book, The Last Governor, was written by journalist Jonathan
Dimbleby with the cooperation of Chris Patten, the last Hong Kong
governor.
</P>
<P>
Newspaper reports in Britain earlier this year said that
Britain's MI6 security service was looking at how Dimbleby came to
have access to information about how the 1987 survey was compiled.
</P>
<P>
But Patten has consistently denied that he leaked official
secrets to the author. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
