<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Sales in UK Rebounded in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 20 (Xinhua) - The Confederation of British
Industry (CBI) reported that sales volumes reached their strongest
level for a year in October after having been held back last month
owing to the death of Diana, Princess of Wales.
</P>
<P>
According to its latest trades survey the level of activity on
the high street last month was well above average for the time of
year, with sales increasing at their quickest rate since November
1996.
</P>
<P>
The CBI said the underlying trend suggested that a slowdown in
sales growth since midsummer has levelled off. Retailers have
became more optimistic about sales prospects for the next few
months.
</P>
<P>
Alastair Eperon, chairman of the CBI's survey panel, said:
"This survey paints a more promising picture for retailers, as
overall sales volumes in October increased at their fastest rate
for almost a year."
</P>
<P>
Official figures, released on Wednesday reveal a surge of 2.8
percent in the volume of goods sold last month after the fall of
1.7 percent recorded in September.
</P>
<P>
The volume of goods sold last month was 6.4 percent higher than
a year earlier, a pace last seen during the 1980s consumer boom.
</P>
<P>
Mark Wall, of Deutsche Morgan Grenfell, said: "The UK consumer
is alive and kicking and looks set to remain robust into next
year."
</P>
<P>
However, economists in the City commonly believe that the
stronger-than-expected rebound, to an annual growth rate of 6.4
percent from 3.8 percent, fuelled fears that the Bank of England
would respond by raising interest rates again to quell
inflationary pressures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
