<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian PM on Probe to Rwanda's Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Prime Minister
Meles Zenawi today urged "the establishment of an international
body of eminent personalities to investigate the genocide in
Rwanda and the surrounding events."
</P>
<P>
He noted that the matter is so serious that there is probably
no greater issue that warrants the urgent attention of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
Over half a million civilians were killed in the genocide
which happened in 1994. Some said up to a million people were
slaughtered in retaliation for the killing of the Rwandan
president when his plane was shot down.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister made the remarks when addressing the
opening session of the 7th ordinary session of the Central Organ
of the OAU Mechanism for Conflict Prevention, Management and
Resolution at ministerial level here.
</P>
<P>
Meles said that "the talk about building our capacity for
early warning and for prevention of conflicts would remain empty
talk if we continue to fail drawing lessons from the most tragic
experience we have had."
</P>
<P>
"The OAU can move forward in the Great Lakes region only if it
has managed to uncover through an objective investigation what
went wrong in Rwanda for the genocide to take place," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian prime minister, the genocide in
Rwanda which has no parallel anywhere in the world since the
Second World War.
</P>
<P>
"This unimaginable tragedy in which close to a million people
were butchered, 95 percent of whom are civilians, including the
very young and the infant," Meles said.
</P>
<P>
He also commended the OAU for its peace initiative in the
African region and OAU members for its efforts so far exerted to
resolve conflicts in their respective sub-regions and in
enhancing OAU's capacity for peace making.
</P>
<P>
In his statement at the opening session, OAU Secretary General
Salim Ahmed Salim said, "the real challenge before us, therefore,
is to ensure that the collective voice of reason and peace is not
drowned by the drums of war, ethnic conflicts and different forms
of intolerance."
</P>
<P>
Salim assessed the current situations in Burundi, Sierra
Leone, Comoros, Somalia and the Republic of Congo, and said,
"Africa cannot shy away from addressing the need to enhance its
capacity to deal with conflict in the continent including
peace-keeping."
</P>
<P>
The opening session was presided by Stan Mudenge, minister of
foreign affairs of Zimbabwe and chairman of this ministerial
session of the central organ. The opening session was followed by
a two-day ministerial meeting in Camera.
</P>
<P>
The Central Organ of the OAU Mechanism for Conflict
Prevention, Management and Resolution was established in 1993 in
Cairo following the first serious deliberation at a summit level
in 1992 in Dakar, Senegal on the need to establish such an organ.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
