<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Urges Abolishment of Illegal Levies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Wu
Bangguo has called for abolishing illegal levies on state-owned
enterprises in order to ease the "heavy burdens" on the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
Improving the economic results of state-owned enterprises has
been and will be conducive to China's campaign to establish a
socialist market economy, and efforts to consolidate the country's
socialist system, according to Wu.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier made the remarks today at a joint government
ministry conference focusing on how to reduce the heavy burden on
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"We must deal seriously with illegal levies on state-owned
enterprises in order maintain social stability and eliminate
corruption amongst officials," said Wu.
</P>
<P>
He said that eliminating levies will be an important step in
meeting the nation's targets for reform the loss-making state
economy and improving the overall economic performance of the
state-owned sector.
</P>
<P>
China hopes to establish a modern enterprise system
encompassing most large and medium-sized enterprises by the end of
this century, and to transform the loss-making sector into
profitable force within three years.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that greater attention must be placed on
reducing illegal levies on state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice-premier also urged government departments to
list and announce illegal levies which will be abolished.
</P>
<P>
The mass media should join in efforts to supervise the related
work of local governments, and nationwide television programs and
teleconferences will be held next year to promote government
efforts to abolish illegal levies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
