<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Unexpected Difficulties for Malaysia's Economy in 1997 (1)  by Wu Dingbao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's economy this
year has been double hit by a turmoil in the financial market and
by an unprecedented haze, resulting in a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's real gross domestic product (GDP) growth is expected
to moderate to 8 percent in 1997 against 8.6 percent in 1996,
according to the government's Economic Report 1997/98 released
recently.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, 1997 is the 10th year for Malaysia to achieve
economic growth at a rate of 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the moderation in Malaysia's economic
growth is mainly due to an envisaged slower pace of economic
activities in the second half of the year following the turmoil in
its foreign exchange and stock markets like other regional markets
triggered by the depreciation of the Thai baht in early July, from
which Malaysia has not been spared.
</P>
<P>
Ringgit, the country's currency, has depreciated by more than
30 percent against the U.S. dollar and share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange have dropped by nearly 50 percent since
then. And both the currency and stock markets are still plunging.
</P>
<P>
The economic situation worsened when Malaysia's tourism, a
promising sector following the depreciation of the local currency,
suffered from the worst ever haze due to forest fires in
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
According to Malaysian Culture, Arts and Tourism Minister
Sabbaruddin Chik, due to the haze which once put Sarawak state in
East Malaysia under an emergency state for 10 days, Malaysia can
not achieve its target of 10 percent increase in tourism revenue
this year as the cancellation rate of hotel rooms reserved by
visitors in East Malaysia is 30 to 40 percent and that in
peninsular Malaysia is as high as 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
The unexpected difficulties confronting the Malaysian economy
this year forced a slowdown of economic activities in almost all
sectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Unexpected difficulties for Malaysia's Economy in 1997 (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As the effects of the financial turbulence will be fully felt
next year, performance of the main sectors of the economy has been
satisfactory as envisaged by the government, with the
manufacturing, construction and some sub-sectors in the service
sector continuing to record double-digit expansion.
</P>
<P>
According to the Economic Report, value added in the
manufacturing sector, the backbone of the economy, is envisaged
to increase by 12 percent in real terms against 12.2 percent in
1996 with its share in  real GDP expected to increase to 35.5
percent in the year against that of 34.2 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Though imposition of the limit on bank lending to the broad
property sector in April and the moderation in demand for
properties discourage new construction starts, value added in the
construction sector is expected to grow by 11 percent in 1997 and
the share of the sector in GDP is expected to increase to 4.8
percent from 4.7 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Growth in value added of the service sector is expected to
remain strong, although at a slower rate of 8.7 percent in 1997
against 9.7 percent in 1996, and the share of service sector in
total GDP is estimated to increase to 45 percent against 44.8
percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Output growth of agriculture, forestry, livestock breeding and
fishery is envisaged to pick up to 3.5 percent this year from 2.2
percent in 1996, the report said, adding its share in GDP however
is expected to continue to slide to 12.2 percent in 1997 from 12.7
percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
This year, Malaysia's current account is estimated to record a
slightly larger deficit of 13.1 billion ringgit (3.93 billion U.S.
dollars), compared with 12.3 billion ringgit (3.69 billion
dollars) in 1996, according to the report. But, as a percentage of
GNP, the current account deficit is envisaged to narrow to 5
percent in 1997 against 5.2 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit is expected to be adequately
financed by net inflow of foreign corporate direct investment,
amounting to 13.2 billion ringgit (3.96 billion dollars), it
said.
</P>
<P>
It is noteworthy that in 1997, Malaysia has been successful in
keeping inflation at a low level, which eased in the first nine
month to 2.6 percent, the lowest since 1990, against 3.6 percent
in the corresponding period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
For 1997 as a whole, inflation rate is estimated to be around 3
percent as the country replenishes its stocks of supplies for the
remaining months of the year with imports at higher prices from
countries whose currencies have appreciated against the ringgit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Unexpected difficulties for Malaysia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Economists say the figures signify that Malaysia's economy is
heading towards a soft landing.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged financial crisis in Southeast Asia will have
significant impact on Malaysia's economy. Therefore, the
government has lowered its projected economic growth to 7 percent
in 1998, and some economists say that the growth rate will be 6 to
6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim, who is also
finance minister, said, "Our economy is at crossroads. The
direction of the economy is currently fraught with uncertainties.
The crisis in the financial markets, which is being experienced,
is a test of economic resilience and the effectiveness of
policies."
</P>
<P>
In the 1998 Budget presented to Parliament in October, the
finance minister laid out strategies to put the economy back on
track -- strengthening economic fundamentals and stabilizing
financial markets; maintaining sustainable growth; continuing the
process of deregulation and liberalization of the economy; and
continuing the social agenda for further overall development.
</P>
<P>
Taking cognizance of loopholes and weaknesses in the economy,
Anwar announced steps accordingly, including cutting government
expenditure by 3 percent; deferring the implementation of several
mega projects with total investments worth 65.6 billion ringgit
(19.68 billion dollars) and tightening supervision over financial
institutions as well as other measures aimed at reducing the
current account deficit, one of the most worrisome weaknesses;
increasing export competitiveness; and discouraging imports by
increasing import duties for luxury items including cars.
</P>
<P>
It is generally believed that the 1998 Budget has set the tone
for overcoming the short-term problems caused by the speculative
assaults on the region's currencies and stock markets.
</P>
<P>
Local economists and analysts are of the view that Malaysia
will most likely see stability over a medium term based on its
strong fundamentals, which, according to them, have not changed
and will not change if not disturbed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
