<HEADLINE> Britain Starts Withdrawing Troops From Northen Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Britain started its first troop
reduction in Northern Ireland today by withdrawing 250 servicemen
from the divided province.
</P>
<P>
This would cut its military presence there to 16,000 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The first contingent of the Parachute Regiment is returning to
their Aldershot base in southern England, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The government said the withdrawal is possible because the
ceasefire between the Irish Republican Army and its pro-British
foes has been respected.
</P>
<P>
However, the troops will be put on alert once the situation
there deteriorates, reports said.
</P>
<P>
"The troops will remain available for recall to the province
should the security situation require it," an army statement said.
</P>
<P>
The pro-British unionists in the province complained that the
troop withdrawal is a concession to Irish republicans while
Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam regarded it as a step toward
normality after years of guerrilla conflicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
