<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Leaders Consider Individuality in Job Creation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The leaders decided that the provisions of the new Amsterdam
Treaty on employment would be put into effect from 1998, but they
agreed that the provisions should be implemented in coordination
with the employment policies of each member state.
</P>
<P>
This approach is seen as a pragmatic one in solving the problem
of unemployment, which has become Europe's biggest headache in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
Majority of the EU leaders are in favor of national plans to
improve training, education and job creation among the young and
long-term unemployed.
</P>
<P>
The European Council meeting also approved two specific
funding initiatives for job creation -- one by the European
Investment Bank to generate extra funds mainly for small and
medium-sized enterprises and the other by the European Parliament
and the Council to help these enterprises create sustainable jobs.
</P>
<P>
The two initiatives will involve more than 30 billion ECUs
(about 36 billion U.S. dollars), according to the draft
resolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
