<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clean Business Crucial to Anti-corruption Fight: ICAC Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Maintaining a clean business
environment is crucial to the Independent Commission Against
Corruption's (ICAC) continued success in combating corruption,
ICAC Commissioner Lily Yam said today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a business ethics conference organized by the
American Chamber of Commerce in conjunction with the ICAC, Yam
stressed the ICAC's care about business ethics.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong is a small and closely knit community. What goes on
in business has a knock-on effect on other aspects of community
life," she said.
</P>
<P>
While business people may be vulnerable to extortion by corrupt
officials, a corrupt business community is just as likely to
whittle away the integrity of the public service, she noted.
</P>
<P>
On the ICAC's part, it has succeeded in encouraging over 1,500
companies to draw up codes of conduct for their staff, which
typically set out the principles and values which govern how a
company conducts its business, and what it expects of its staff.
</P>
<P>
"The next step is for us to persuade these companies to
integrate these values and principles in their decision making
process," she added.
</P>
<P>
She took pride in pointing to the fact that Hong Kong has
evolved into the major international financial and business center
that it is today, partly because of its success in fighting
corruption.
</P>
<P>
"We are firmly committed to this task (of keeping corruption
under control)," she reassured, calling for the business community
to do its part as well.
</P>
<P>
Other speakers at the conference included Secretary for Justice
Elsie Leung, President of the Chinese Manufacturers' Association
of Hong Kong Herbert Liang and some other senior business
executives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
