<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton warily welcomed Saddam Hussein's
decision to back down and allow inspectors to resume their search
for weapons of mass destruction in Iraq. Arab leaders expressed
relief over the agreement that appears to have averted the threat
of a military confrontation.
</P>
<P>
-- The militant Islamic Group, which has claimed responsibility
for the attack that killed 58 foreign tourists in Luxor, taunted
the Egyptian Government, which it has said was its real target.
The organization said it might be willing to halt its military
operations, but only if the Government took certain steps.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- The United Nations Thursday night told its weapons
inspectors to return to Iraq on Friday after Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein apparently ended his defiance of the world body and
averted a possible military confrontation with the United States
by reversing a ban on American members of the inspection team.
</P>
<P>
-- South Korean has become the latest and largest country in
East Asia to surrender to the financial crisis sweeping the
region and seek an international bailout. The rescue package
could be the biggest in history, economists said.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- proposed health-care protections were accepted by Clinton,
who urged the medical industry to adopt an advisory commission's
report and said Congress should pass legislation to ensure all
consumers are covered. Republican leaders immediately accused the
president of trying to revive his failed health-care plan.
</P>
<P>
-- AIDS researchers believe they have found why some people
infected with the virus never develop the full-blown disease. A
Massachusetts study in today's Science found some people have
unusually high levels of helper T-cells that specifically target
the virus, suggesting very early intervention to protect such
cells could help. 
</P>
</TEXT>
