<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nebiolo Introduces Golden League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 21 (Xinhua) -- A new Golden League including
six elite meetings will be introduced next season, International
Amateur Athletic Federation president Primo Nebiolo announced in
Monte Carlo Friday.
</P>
<P>
Nebiolo said the Golden League would include the most
successful of the existing Grand Prix meetings: Berlin, Brussels,
Monte Carlo, Oslo, Rome and Zurich. The Paris meeting might also
be included if it can match the prize money being offered.
</P>
<P>
The Golden League will have a jackpot of one million dollars to
be divided equally amongst all athletes winning his or her Golden
League events and the Grand Prix final.
</P>
<P>
In the absence of a jackpot winner, the prize of the overall
Grand Prix will be allocated under the existing structure of
200,000 dollars for first place, 100,000 dollars for second,
50,000 dollars for third.
</P>
<P>
World record breakers in the Golden League events will receive
a bonus of 50,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Nebiolo said the IAAF wanted prize money to be a bigger
incentive than appearance fees, however, the world's best
athletes would be offered special promotional agreements to
encourage them to compete in the Golden League.
</P>
<P>
The new series should be sanctioned by the IAAF Council this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
The League replaces the Golden Four meetings at Zurich,
Cologne, Brussels and Berlin which invariably drew the best
fields and put up a 20kg gold ingot divided between competitors
who won their specialty event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Taiwan-Funded Projects in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The number of Taiwan-funded
projects in Shanghai, China's largest industrial center, topped
3,000 by the end of July, according to a local official in charge
of Taiwan affairs.
</P>
<P>
The projects, with a contracted value of three billion
U.S. dollars, accounted for 12.5 percent of the total value of
foreign-funded project in Shanghai, according to Qiu Changgen,
deputy secretary-general of the Shanghai Municipal Society of
Taiwan Affairs. Qiu made the remarks during the recent Fourth
Shanghai-Taiwan Seminar.
</P>
<P>
The influx of Taiwan investments in Shanghai has passed through
three stages: the initial period between 1984-1990 which ended
with the establishment of a mere 108 Taiwan-funded firms; the boom
period from 1991 and 1994 which witnessed the arrival of 2,050
Taiwan firms; and the period of smooth development in place since
1995. Some 70 percent of Taiwan-funded projects are small
industrial enterprises in various sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
