<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rule of Law Central to HK's Success: Secretary for Justice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The rule of law is one of
the fundamental elements of Hong Kong's legal system that help to
foster ethical business conduct in Hong Kong, a senior official of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a keynote luncheon speech at a conference of
"Business Ethics in the HKSAR", Elsie Leung Oi-sie, HKSAR's
secretary for justice, said that the rule of law has been central
to Hong Kong's economic and social success.
</P>
<P>
One of the principles of the rule of law is that laws operate
separately from the political system, Leung said.
</P>
<P>
The second principle is that everyone, no matter how high, is
subject to the law, and that a person can only be punished for
conduct that is a breach of the law, she said.
</P>
<P>
The third principle is that of equality before the law: no one
gets better or worse treatment under the law because of his or her
status, wealth, race and so on, Leung said.
</P>
<P>
For the business community in particular, the rule of law is
crucial. Without it, there is no protection against corruption,
nepotism or expropriation.
</P>
<P>
Only under the rule of law are businessmen guaranteed the level
playing field and the competitive environment which they need, she
added.
</P>
<P>
"The independence of the Judiciary is another cornerstone of
our legal system that promotes ethical behavior," Leung said. In
the SAR, judicial independence is secured by provisions in the
Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law stipulates that the courts of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region shall exercise power independently,
free from any interference.
</P>
<P>
During her speech, Leung elaborated some specific areas of the
law that foster ethical business conduct, which include
anti-corruption legislation, control of unfair contract terms, and
anti-discrimination laws.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0068 </DOCNO>
