<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: South Korea Turns to IMF for Rescue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 21 (Xinhua) -- South Korea, which has been
called a "tiger" for its booming economy, today formally applied
to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) for a loan of 50 billion
U.S. dollars to bail out its plunging financial market.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean currency won has sharply devaluated since the
beginning of October, breaking the mark of 1,000 against the
dollar and sending the stock price index to the lowest level of
under 500 points since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners have been either withdrawing their investment from
the country or scrambling to convert their holdings into dollars.
</P>
<P>
While political turmoil relating to the December 18
presidential election played a part in worsening the financial
situation, economic recession which started in late 1995 has been
the principal villain.
</P>
<P>
First, the poor management of some large conglomerates has
brought about huge amounts of non-performancing loans and bad
loans. These conglomerates have been given all kinds of privileges
including huge government loans in the country's 40 years of
development and become a dominant player in the economy.
</P>
<P>
Their management characterized by high cost, low efficiency and
blind expansion has made the mostly export-oriented conglomerates
increasingly less competitive in the world market.
</P>
<P>
Several business giants have collapsed under heavy debt burden
since the beginning of this year, seriously weakening foreign
investors' confidence in the economy.
</P>
<P>
Government policy flaws are also to blame. The government has
been controlling the financial market with strict rules. Critics
say the government has put too much emphasis on such numerical
economic indicators as GDP growth rate, export growth rate and
inflation rate, ignoring institutional issues like competition
rules and the efficiency of market structure.
</P>
<P>
Big current account deficit and foreign debt, a price the
country has paid for economic growth, is also a catalyst. The
financial crisis, which started in Thailand and then spread to
other South-east Asian nations, brought a strong negative impact
on South Korea's financial market.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the IMF is certainly a painful decision. It could
mean more business bankruptcies, less economic sovereignty and
high unemployment. But with the presidential election less than a
month away, what else can the incumbent government do to contain
the situation? 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IAAF To Practise New Golden League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The International Amateur
Athletic Federation (IAAF) will adopt a Golden League next year
which feature six or seven meetings within the current grand prix
circuit.
</P>
<P>
IAAF president Primo Nebiolo announced the news here on Friday,
saying that the meetings will include Rome, Oslo, Monaco, Zurich,
Brussels, Berlin and possibly Paris.
</P>
<P>
The president said that under the Golden League a total of one
million U.S. dollars will be shared among winners in each of the
meetings along with champions at the grand prix final in Moscow on
September 5.
</P>
<P>
A bonus of $50,000 will be awarded to those who break a world
record at a Golden League meeting. 
</P>
