<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most State-Sponsored Overseas Scholars Return on Time (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 21 (Xinhua) -- China's new practise of
sending scholars abroad for advanced training at state expense has
been successful, with 90 percent scholars returning home on
schedule.
</P>
<P>
"The new method has helped improve both the quality of scholars
and the return rate, " according to Cao Guoxing, secretary-general
of the China Scholarship Council (CSC). Cao made the remarks
during today's annual meeting of the CSC.
</P>
<P>
China has subsidized foreign studies for 1,107 people since
1995 when the nation introduced reform in northeast China's Jilin
Province and east China's Jiangsu Provinces. The CSC was formed in
1996 to administer related affairs on behalf of the State
Education Commission.
</P>
<P>
The reform effort has allowed individuals to apply for state
subsidies for studies and research outside China. Experts review
applications, with a panel of at least five experts rendering
final approval.
</P>
<P>
Individuals approved for foreign studies or research sign
contracts with the CSC and deposit a specified amount of earnest
money in designated banks prior to going abroad.
</P>
<P>
Scholars returning on time can claim the earnest money and
accumulated interest. Those failing to fulfill contract
commitments are subject to fines.
</P>
<P>
The new system is the first in Chinese history requiring
scholars receiving state subsidies to sign a legally binding
contract prior to going abroad.
</P>
<P>
"Contracts has altered the situation under which the state or
sponsor lacked a binding agreement with people receiving
subsidies," said Cao.
</P>
<P>
The CSC has adjudicated a number of cases involving contract
violations, and in so doing has guaranteed administrative
supervision over the efficient use of state funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Samson Retains WBF Junior Bantamweight Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 21 (Xinhua) -- World Boxing Federation (WBF)
junior bantamweight champion Samson Dutchboygym of Thailand
retained his title with a technical knockout victory over South
Korea's Jin Young Yung in Sukhothai, Thailand, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Samson's 21st title defence ended two minutes into the fourth
round when the referee stopped the fight after Jin, 26, received
his second eight-count of the round.
</P>
<P>
Samson, 25, dominated the fight with left hooks to the body and
 left and right hooks to the face.
</P>
<P>
The lanky Jin fought well with left jabs and right hooks to the
face but was unable to match the more powerful Thai, who took
control in the third round.
</P>
<P>
Samson now has 26 wins (23 KOs) under his belt, while Jin's
record stands at eight wins (four KOs) and five losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
