<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most State-Sponsored Overseas Scholars Return on Time (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The CSC has adopted procedures enabling returned scholars to
apply for research funds. The system is designed to serve the
country and ensure that scholars return on time.
</P>
<P>
CSC members attending today's meeting proposed that the
organization provide additional funds for state-sponsored overseas
scholars and establish a reasonable scholarship system.
</P>
<P>
CSC members also discussed issues related to sending more
scholars abroad for advanced studies without requesting additional
government funding.
</P>
<P>
The CSC has attempted to solve related issues by cooperating
with local governments. Agreements reached between the CSC and
local governments in June yielded three million yuan (360,000 US
dollars) in funding to sponsor scholars for overseas study and
academic exchange programs.
</P>
<P>
North China's Hebei and northeast China's Liaoning provinces
have pledged to pay half the expenses of scholars engaged in
overseas programs. The agreements have effectively relieved the
CSC of burdens related to paying the full amount.
</P>
<P>
The CSC announced that it will initiate a program sponsoring
Chinese students seeking master's degrees abroad. The organization
has also reduced the time limit for senior visiting scholars to
remain overseas from 12 months to 3-6 months.
</P>
<P>
The CSC will also relax age limits for applicants in order to
provide outstanding students with an opportunity to study abroad.
</P>
<P>
The CSC will improve administrative efficiency by establishing
links with the Internet in order to provide direct links with
foreign scholars.
</P>
<P>
The CSC is currently drafting plans to send scholars abroad in
1998. Informed sources note that the number of applicants approved
will remain at the 1997 level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
