<HEADLINE> Suspects of Shooting Attack Arrested in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli security forces
today arrested a number of suspects in the East Jerusalem area,
who were in connection with Wednesday's shooting attack on Jewish
students in Jerusalem's Old City.
</P>
<P>
Israeli police believed that the suspects belong to a local
gang of terrorists who received help from residents of the
Muslim quarter in the Old City.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a temporary police post has been set up beside the
Jewish religious school in the Old City and police personnel in
the area have been increased to provide protection for the
Jewish residents.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu Thursday described
the attack, in which a Jewish student was killed and another was
seriously wounded, as an unprecedented act of terrorism that was
"intolerable" and must not go unpunished.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu noted that the assailants used Kalashnikov automatic
rifles, stressing that this was a grave escalation in the type
of weaponry used by terrorists operating in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
On the Palestinian side, Hisham Abdul Razik, a Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) official in the joint
Israeli-Palestinian security committee, Thursday condemned the
shooting, saying that "all acts of violence hurt the peace
process and have negative effects."
</P>
<P>
PNA security sources said that Netanyahu's hardline policy in
the peace process should be blamed for the shooting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
