<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Down Cuba to Remain Unbeaten </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 21 (Xinhua) -- European champions Russia
overpowered out-formed Olympic and world champions Cuba to
continue their winning streak through four rounds at the women's
competition of the world volleyball grand champions cup tournament
here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The showdown between the two favorites, both unbeaten in their
first three actions, turned into an one-side game as Russia's
young talent Evguenia Artamonova smashed all the way to power her
team to 15-9, 13-15, 15-6, 15-9 over Cuba in one hour and 31
minutes.
</P>
<P>
With a 4-0 record, the Russians has virtually gained the title
of the six-team event even if they lose their last match to South
Korea on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
South Korea suffered its fourth setback in as many outings
after going down to Asian champions China 15-6, 12-15, 15-9 on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, trailing 10-1 in the second set, fought bravely to
narrow the gap to 13-10, before the game heading to rally-point
system under the new rule of the 25-minute time limitation.
</P>
<P>
Both sides went steadily on their chances of scoring, and
China's top spiker Sun Yue leaped to the net and sealed the set
with her over-blocking samsh.
</P>
<P>
"Entirely, we played well but our attacking combination didn't
work well on the half way of the second set." Chinese head coach
Lang Ping said at a post-press conference.
</P>
<P>
"We lost to China 3-0 few months ago at the Asian Championship
and so did we today. We are in our worst condition caused by
losing key players and injuries to others," said Kim Hyung-sil,
 head coach of the winless South Korea.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, China will face Brazil, a 3-0 winner over hosts
Japan, to decide the third place behind Russia and Cuba in their
fifth and final match at the round robin tournament.
</P>
<P>
Northern American champions Brazil scored a 2-2 win-lost record
after beating Japan 15-13, 15-1 and 15-4 in Friday's last match.
</P>
<P>
Saturday will see the men's fifth round which features China vs
host Japan, Cuba vs Australia and Brazil vs The Netherlands.
</P>
</TEXT>
