<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Marks 25th Anniversary of Okinawa's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government held a
ceremony in Okinawa today to mark the 25th anniversary of the
return of the island prefecture to Japan from the United States,
according to a Kyodo News report.
</P>
<P>
Some 700 dignitaries, including Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto, attended the commemorative ceremony at the Okinawa
convention Center in the City of Ginowan, report reaching here
said.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was held on the date when the United States and
Japan issued a joint statement in 1969 announcing an end to
U.S. occupation.
</P>
<P>
Okinawa was officially returned to Japan on May 15, 1972 after
27 years of the U.S. occupation since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
Japan failed to hold the commemorative ceremony in May because
of the dispute between Okinawa Prefecture and the central
government over the continued land use for U.S. military
facilities in the southernmost island prefecture.
</P>
<P>
But the government-sponsored ceremony today failed to create a
festive mood because major local political parties and civic
groups were boycotting the event to draw attention to Okinawa's
sluggish economy and the heavy U.S. presence.
</P>
<P>
Okinawa, accounting for only 0.6 percent of Japan's total area,
houses about 75 percent of U.S. military presence in Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three More Golds for South Korea at Taekwondo Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 21 (Xinhua) -- South Korea won three out of
 four gold medals at stake on the third day to top gold medal
tally with six at the 13th Men's and Sixth Women's Taekwondo World
Championships here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
China's Liu Chuang won his country's first ever world
championships medal, a bronze medal, today.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's defending champion Dong Wan Lee won the men's
middle weight category final, beating Cuban Alefredo Escobar
Osorio.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's world championships debutee Eyun Joung Woo, 19,
took the women's middle weight category title after beating
Morocco's Bourguigue Mounia, 19, in the final.
</P>
<P>
The silver medal won by Mounia, seven-time national champion
and one-time Arabian champion, is the first ever world
championships medal for her country.
</P>
<P>
Another world championships debutee from South Korea, Eun Suk
Hwang, won the women's bantam weight category by defeating
Canadian Roxane Forget in the final.
</P>
<P>
And the only gold medal which eluded from South Korean hands
today was that in the men's bantam weight category. Chinese
Taipei's Huang Chih-Hsiung, brone-medalist from the 1995 world
champioships, took the gold after beating Iranian Mehdi Bibak Asl
in the final.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Liu Chuang tied for the third place with Oscar Salazar
Blanco from Mexico in the categry. China introduced the sport
only three years ago and has had a national team just for a bit
more than one year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
