<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade between S. Africa, Indonesia Develops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 21 (Xinhua)-- Visiting Indonesian President
Mohamed Suharto today visited an Indonesian trade fair at Cape Town's
civic center, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Suharto appeared relaxed as he chatted to some of the 30
Indonesian producers who are exhibiting their products which include
include leather, canned and frozen sea food, wooden and rattan
furniture, glassware, textiles and batik.
</P>
<P>
From almost a zero base in the last five years, two-way trade
between Indonesia and South Africa has grown to 258 million U.S.
Ddollars with the balance in South Africa's favor, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Trade relations between the two countries have been hampered by the
absence of direct transport links and the lack of formal agreement to
facilitate economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, however, at the start of Suharto's three-day state
visit to South Africa, bilateral agreements on trade and aviation were
reportedly signed to boost bilateral trade. 
