<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Increase Afforestation Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 21 (Xinhua) -- A Ministry of Forestry
official attending today's session of the ongoing international
environmental conference said that China will raise its
afforestation rate from less than 14 to over 20 percent in 13
years.
</P>
<P>
The country will also have less biological degradation by year
2010 due to programs controlling soil erosion and desertification,
according to Li Yucai, vice-minister of Forestry.
</P>
<P>
Li made the remarks during today's closing session of the '97
China Environmental Forum.
</P>
<P>
China has increased its forestry coverage by some six percent
from the eight percent coverage level 45 years ago, according to
Li.
</P>
<P>
"The country will reach its goal by maintaining the current
rate of afforestation and deforestation," said Li Shidong, a
ministry official in the afforestation program.
</P>
<P>
China has 134 million hectares of forests, representing a total
of 11.8 billion cubic meters of timber, according to Li. The per
capita level of timber is only one-sixth of the worldwide
average. However, the country plants trees on 8.8 million hectares
of land or hills annually.
</P>
<P>
Li Yucai noted that relevant departments are drafting national
environmental protection programs focusing on the Yangtze and
Yellow river valleys and the loess plateau. The forestry ministry
will introduce six new afforestation projects to areas in the
aforementioned river valleys over 12 months.
</P>
<P>
The government also plans to increase the coverage of nature
reserves from the current 6.37 percent to 8.33 percent of the
nation's total territory in order to protect wildlife and
endangered species, according to the official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
