<HEADLINE> UN Arms Inspectors Return to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations' 77 arms
inspectors, including the expelled Americans, returned to Iraq
today, ending a three-week standoff between Iraq and the U.N..
</P>
<P>
U.N. sources, who asked not to be named, said the inspectors
arrived at Iraq's Habaniya military air base, about 120 kilometers
west of the capital Baghdad, from Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to resume inspection on Iraq's weapons
systems Saturday, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
The inspectors pulled out of Iraq on November 14 after Iraq
expelled the six Americans in the U.N. inspection teams a day
before. After intensive diplomatic moves, Iraq accepted a Russian
proposal Thursday to allow the inspectors to be back.
</P>
<P>
The inspectors working for the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM)
are overseeing the elimination of Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council will not lift the crippling sanctions
it imposed on Iraq since 1990 until the commission has verified
that Iraq has complied with U.N. orders.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler has announced he
will soon return to Baghdad for talks with Iraqi officials on the
inspection of sensitive sites where inspectors have earlier been
denied entry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
