<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developed Nations Should Reduce Greenhouse Gas Emissions, Experts Say (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Developed countries,
which are the biggest source of global greenhouse gas, should
be responsible for reducing greenhouse gas emissions, according to
scientists at the '97 China Environmental Forum in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
R. Estrada Oyuela, Chairman of the Ad Hoc Group Berlin Mandate
of UN Framework Convention on Climate Change, said that
developed nations should take the lead in global efforts to cut
greenhouse gas emissions.
</P>
<P>
Greenhouse gas emissions in developing countries are much lower
than in developed countries and countries with economies in
transition, in both absolute and per-capita terms, according to
Robert T. Watson, chairman of the Intergovernmental Panel on
Climate Change (IPCC) and director of the World Bank's Environment
Department.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 64 percent of the global greenhouse gas was emitted
by developed countries, which account for only 25 percent of the
world's population.
</P>
<P>
What is more, Watson pointed out, developed countries have a
much greater economic, technological and institutional capability
to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
"We must all recognize that, in the near-term, developing
countries need to increase their production and consumption of
energy to alleviate poverty and under-development," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zou Jingmeng, former head of the World Meteorological
Organization, said that, although dealing with greenhouse gas
is a common responsibility, developed countries should do more in
this regard.
</P>
<P>
Zou urged developed countries to fulfill their commitments in
accordance with the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change.
</P>
<P>
At the UN Conference on Environment and Development in 1992,
developed countries were called on to reduce greenhouse gas
emissions to the 1990 level by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
However, judged by current trends, greenhouse gas emissions in
developed countries still fall short of the standard, according to
Dr. Suvit Yodmani, director and regional representative of the UN
Environment Program for Asia and the Pacific.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developed Nations Should Reduce Greenhouse Gas Emissions (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He added that more financial and technical assistance
should be provided to developing countries to help them control
greenhouse gas emissions.
</P>
<P>
In December, leaders of various countries will meet in Japan to
discuss climate changes, and an agreement on the reduction of
greenhouse gas emissions is expected to be reached then.
</P>
<P>
Japan and the European Union recently said that they would cut
greenhouse gas emissons 2.5 and 15 percent respectively by the
year 2010.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang Zhijia, director of the International
Co-operation Department of the State Bureau of Environmental
Protection, China has made great efforts in the past decade in
improving energy utilization, restructuring energy consumption,
developing new clean energy, afforestation and population control.
</P>
<P>
"Actually we have made great contributions to the global
reduction of greenhouse gas emissions," Wang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
