<HEADLINE> South Asian Countries to Speed up Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The seven member countries
of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC)
have decided to accelerate economic and trade cooperation, said a
press release issued today by the Kathmandu-based SAARC
Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The recent meeting of the SAARC's Committee on Economic
Cooperation (CEC) held in Male, capital of the Maldives, stressed
the need for liberalization of visa procedures for traders and
businessmen and the completion of the third round of trade
negotiations under the South Asian Preferential Trading
Arrangement by early 1998, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Maldivian Minister of Trade, Industries and
Labor Abdulla Yameen highlighted the need for greater attention to
the SAARC's least developed countries, namely, Bangladesh, Bhutan,
Nepal and the Maldives, in the ongoing third round of trade
negotiations which aims to achieve a South Asian Free Trade Area
(SAFTA) by 2001 as decided at the May SAARC Summit.
</P>
<P>
The second meeting of the SAARC's Inter-Governmental Expert
Group on Transition to SAFTA held on October 21 in Kathmandu
formulated an action plan which will serve as a blueprint for
trade negotiations by the Inter-Governmental Group on Trade
Liberalization.
</P>
<P>
The CEC meeting discussed the arrangements for convening the
second meeting of the SAARC commerce ministers and the second
SAARC trade fair scheduled for next year, said the press release.
</P>
<P>
The CEC's recommendations will be submitted to the forthcoming
session of the SAARC Council of Ministers to be held in the
Maldives on November 29-30, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
The other three members of the SAARC are India, Pakistan and
Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
