<HEADLINE> Debt-Laden Japanese Stores Close in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 21 (Xinhua) -- All the nine Yaohan
department stores in Hong Kong closed today because the troubled
Japanese chain retailer failed to pay its debts.
</P>
<P>
The shutdown would throw 2,700 staff out of work, the
largest-scale layoff in Hong Kong's retail industry.
</P>
<P>
Yaohan Hong Kong Corporation Ltd announced Thursday that its
wholly-owned subsidiary, Yaohan Department Store (HK), had applied
to the High Court of Hong Kong for its winding up because it could
not pay its debts. There were nine Yaohan department stores in
Hong Kong and one in Macao, all closed today.
</P>
<P>
Three people from the accounting firm Ernst &AMP; Young had been
appointed as provisional liquidators, said Yaohan, owned by the
Japanese Wada family.
</P>
<P>
The retailer giant moved its headquarters from Japan to Hong
Kong in 1990 to expand its business in Hong Kong, Macao and the
Chinese inland areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
