<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stock Rebounds Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong share prices
rebounded nearly 500 points today to end the volatile week at
10,548.20 following the overnight surge in Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The jump recouped all the lost ground over the past three days,
when the key Hang Seng Index took an accumulative loss of 369
points after a sharp rise of 462 points on Monday amid the concern
that the plunge of the South Korean won and the Malaysian ringgit
could test the Hong Kong dollar again.
</P>
<P>
The Dow-Jones 500 Industrial Index rose sharply to surpass
7,800 points last night, triggering a higher open on the Hong Kong
bourse this morning.
</P>
<P>
Easing interest rates on the local money market turned out to
be another engine of today's recovery, in which the blue-chip
index went up 497.52 points, or 4.95 percent. The primary
three-month interbank lending rates came down to around ten
percent, creating encouraging sentiment in the market.
</P>
<P>
Bank counters led the rebound today by rocketing more than 700
points, or 5.7 percent, while utilities, property, and commerce
and industry shares all posted considerable gains of four to five
percent. Red chips rose slightly but H shares edged lower.
</P>
<P>
Volume turned up to about 11.08 billion HK dollars (1.42
billion US dollars) from the seven-month low of 7.516 billion HK
dollars (963 million US dollars) on Thursday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
