<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania May Have Independent Graft Prosecutor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian
government is considering the possibility of appointing an
independent prosecutor to try cases related to corruption in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Dar es Salaam Thursday,
President Benjamin Mkapa said he has not decided on the matter
but he was seriously thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
"The use of an independent prosecutor to try corruption cases
is one of the issues currently lying on my desk. We have not
decided on it, but certainly we are taking it seriously and
thinking on the possibility of adopting it," he was quoted by The
Guardian as saying.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutor is to operate under the Prevention of
Corruption Bureau. The bureau, which would reclaim powers of
arrest, search and detention under recent amendments to the law,
is currently responsible for the investigation of the corruption
cases, but it must wait for the authority from the Director of
Public Prosecutors (DPP) to try the suspects.
</P>
<P>
Appointment of a special prosecutor independent of the DPP is
that it would overcome the apparent delay in clearing the cases
in hand for prosecution, and the possibility of some of them
being suppressed, Daily News said.
</P>
<P>
President Mkapa reiterated his commitment to fight corruption,
but asked for a wider support to accomplish the mission.
</P>
<P>
"Let them (corrupt officials) rest assured that they have no
sanctuary at all," he warned. "Once we've evidence about their
involvement in corruption we will immediately take them to task."
</P>
<P>
The president also assured that he keeps telling members of
the Cabinet to be transparent and honest when conducting
government business.
</P>
<P>
He said he has not completed his crusade to bring changes in
the government. He did not elaborate but insisted that he was not
through.
</P>
<P>
"Let us wait and see what is going to happen in the next few
weeks," Mkapa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
