<HEADLINE> China's Military Technology Serves for Environment Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 21 (Xinhua) -- China's departments of
science and technology for national defense have made important
contributions to environmental protection with their nuclear,
aerospace and remote-sensing technologies.
</P>
<P>
Li Jinai, an official from the Commission of Science, Technology
and Industry for National Defense (COSTIND), said today at the
"1997 China Environment Forum" which concludes this evening that
COSTIND will expand cooperation with the financial and business
sectors both at home and abroad to push the application of
military sciences to the civilian fields.
</P>
<P>
Wang Tongye, vice-minister in charge of COSTIND, said the
military science and technology departments have utilized isotopes
in fire control and remote-sensing technology in surveys of
resources, environmental monitoring and natural disaster
prediction.
</P>
<P>
Military science departments have also developed complete sets
of equipment for disposing urban sewage and garbage transfer.
</P>
<P>
Wu Fengshu, general engineer of the China National Nuclear Corp.,
said his company has 24 ventures for producing isotopes
and isotope instruments, with a total annual output of more than
100 million yuan (12 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Wu said his company's automatic fire-alarm devices and
fire-control systems have a 70 percent share of the domestic
market.
</P>
<P>
Wang Tongye said environmental protection will be the major
field for the applications of military sciences and
technologies.
</P>
<P>
China's national defense science and technology departments
hope to contribute more to the mankind, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
