<HEADLINE> OECD Countries Reach Anti-Corruption Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The 29 member countries of the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD)
reached an agreement early this morning to ban enterprises from
bribing foreign countries in exchange for contracts.
</P>
<P>
Talks on an OECD convention on fighting corruption started on
Tuesday in the headquarters of the OECD in Paris, according to
Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted Alan Larson, the assistant secretary for economic and
trade affairs of the United States State Department, as saying that
the results of the talks are ``remarkable'' for OECD and for the
countries which wish to join this convention.
</P>
<P>
He said that although there are still some ``points of
suspension'' in the agreement, it makes up a ``big step forward''
in fighting corruption in international business field.
</P>
<P>
A partial solution has been found to the problem of bribing
political parties of foreign countries by enterprises of OECD
countries, and OECD governments will make emergency efforts in
this regard, said Larson. 
</P>
