<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Quickened Economic Reform Envisaged in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has put
a final touch to preparations for beefing up economic reforms in
the coming year when presidential election will be held for the
first time in five years.
</P>
<P>
The Fourth Nigerian Economic Summit ended in the capital Abuja
Thursday with participants faulting the 1997 budget to be
"structurally defective" and recommending a wide range of reforms
next year.
</P>
<P>
The annual meeting attended by senior government officials,
economists, industrialists, experts and scholars, among others,
is a forum before the government finalizes its fiscal budget.
</P>
<P>
In a 49-page summary of discussions at the summit, the
participants noted that the 1997 budget relied heavily on the
public sector to jump-start the economy instead of the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
Among the wide range of reforms recommended are the proposals
on education, health and population put forward to by the Vision
2010, the country's first long-term socio-economic development
blueprint no waiting for the "Go ahead" instruction from the head
of state.
</P>
<P>
These reforms should be integrated into the 1998 budget,
participants said.
</P>
<P>
The summit document rated government low on the implementation
of this year's budget, pointing at delayed capital spending by
government and excess liquidity at the beginning of the year,
followed by too much fiscal tightening later in the year as part
of its defects.
</P>
<P>
Head of State General Sani Abacha, at the opening of the
summit Wednesday, also admitted that the economy did not perform
as expected in 1997 as for increasing more jobs was concerned.
</P>
<P>
The government effort to build up a healthy economy this year
has resulted in comparatively stable macroeconomic stability
characterized by diving inflation rate, increasing foreign
exchange reserves, falling foreign debt stocks and stable
exchange rate of the local currency to hard currencies.
</P>
<P>
However, lack of development of infrastructure facilities has
contributed to the poor performance of the manufacturing sector
so that most industrial products have to be imported to meet
domestic need.
</P>
<P>
The expensive imported goods plus the poor pay of public
sector employees and high unemployment have resulted in low
purchasing power and subsequently low consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
Very little tax/tariff reforms, lack of bold steps to further
liberalize/deregulate the economy, non abrogation of laws
inhibiting competition are all factors to the sluggishness of the
economy this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to statistics, about 70 percent of the
country's private wealth which could have given a boost to
domestic economic growth is being kept abroad.
</P>
<P>
Observers noted how to persuade the owners of the wealth, the sum
of which is unknown but believed to be very big, will remain an
important job of the government.
</P>
<P>
Although he was not happy with the private sector which has
not been active enough to invest, Abacha said his administration
will try to ensure that private investment will be worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
To achieve improvement next year, Abacha has promised that the
government will work towards providing enabling environment from
1998 and in subsequent years for the manufacturing industry to
rise up to the challenges of developing Nigeria's abundant
domestic resources and providing employment for the teeming
population.
</P>
<P>
As presidential election is drawing near, Abacha, whether he
is to contest or not, is sure to take some measures to better the
economy and the people's daily life.
</P>
<P>
It is the only way to keep the situation stable for such an
extraordinarily important year in the history of the country.
</P>
<P>
Abacha has stated his government is committed to the speedy
and faithful implementation of the recommendations of the Vision
2010 Committee into the 1988 budget in order to accelerate
economic growth and long-term development of the country.
</P>
<P>
This might be a good thing and the people are waiting to see
what economic measures the government is to take in the new
budget which is expected to be announced before the end of this
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
