<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Release 75 Detainees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government may
eventually grant amnesty to 75 political detainees, including
Boshorun M.K.O. Abiola, the alleged winner of the annulled 1993
election.
</P>
<P>
The Vanguard newspaper reported today that a special committee
has begun a screening of the detainees and will make its
recommendations to the government as to who will be let free.
</P>
<P>
Members of the special committee include the Inspector-General
of the Police, Alhaji Ibrahim Coomassie, National Adviser on
Security, Alhaji Ibrahim Gwarzo, Special Adviser to the Head of
State on Legal Matters and Political Affairs, Awalu Yadudu and
others, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's head of state, General Sani Abacha announced Monday
in a national broadcast marking his four years in power that the
government will grant amnesty to detainees whose release will no
longer pose impediments to the peace and security of the country.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a source as saying that the head of state is
quite determined to release all the detainees, and will give
Nigerians a surprise.
</P>
<P>
The report added that with the speed of the work, the actual
release of the detainees might be effected this weekend.
</P>
<P>
Among the prominent detainees whose release has been much
canvassed in the past are M.K.O. Abiola, the millionaire
politician who has been in jail since 1994; former head of state
Olusegun Obasanjo, jailed for his role in a failed coup in 1995
and a number of union leaders and journalists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
