<HEADLINE> India's UF Rejects Congress Demand to Sack DMK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The 14-party United Front
(UF) today rejected the Congress demand to oust three ministers of
Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam (DMK), one of the constituents of the
UF, from the Gujral government.
</P>
<P>
The core committee of the UF held a meeting at the residence of
Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral here this morning to discuss a
letter given to Gujral by Congress President Sitaram Kesri last
night, who asked the prime minister to choose between DMK and the
Congress.
</P>
<P>
The letter said that the Congress cannot continue to extend its
support to the UF government if the DMK continues to be a
constituent of the government.
</P>
<P>
A report presented to Parliament by the Jain Commission said
that the DMK was linked with the assassination of former prime
minister Rajiv Gandhi in 1991.
</P>
<P>
"It does not matter whether the government stays or goes, but
the DMK will stay," said a UF leader.
</P>
<P>
Former prime minister Deve Gowda today also said that whether
there were general elections or not, there was no question of
dumping the DMK from the government.
</P>
<P>
Congress President Kesri today declined to comment on the UF's
decision to reject his party's demand for sacking the three
ministers of the DMK from the UF government.
</P>
<P>
He said that he could react only after he was formally informed
by the front of its decision.
</P>
<P>
Congress senior leader in the Lower House of Parliament Sharad
Pawar said today that his party was prepared to face polls in the
event of the fall of the UF government.
</P>
<P>
The UF core committee is expected to meet here again this
evening to further discuss the present situation in the country.
</P>
