<HEADLINE> 19 More Kenyans Die of Cholera </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 21 (Xinhua) -- At least 19 more Kenyans died
of cholera spreading fast in western and coastal Kenya this week,
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Another 12 people in the country's second-largest city
Mombasa, Coast Province, have been killed by cholera in the past
two days.
</P>
<P>
The death toll since the disease broke out late October in
Mombasa and nearby tourist resort Malindi has reached 30.
</P>
<P>
The disease has also killed four people in Kisumu, the third
largest city of the country alongside Lake Victoria and three in
Busia, the town bordering on Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Mombasa District commissioner Paul Olando said the situation
is still serious there and warned all Mombasa residents to
support the government campaign to keep out fast-spreading
cholera by observing simple hygiene rules.
</P>
<P>
Most of the deaths have occurred in Changamwe, Mombasa where
the government has sent a special team of experts to handle the
situation.
</P>
<P>
Medical personnel said they are fearing that the toll from the
epidemic could rise following the heavy rains currently pounding
coastal, central and western Kenya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
