<HEADLINE> E. Africa to Tighten Defense Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The chiefs of Defense
of Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania have agreed on a draft memorandum
of joint understanding, including military training and disaster
handling operations.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum, signed at a meeting Thursday in Arusha, in
north Tanzania, also proposes deepening of co-operation in
defence among the three member states, Daily News said today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by General Robert Mboma, Chief of the
Tanzanian People's Defense Forces, General Dauydi Tonje, Chief of
General Staff of Kenya Armed Forces and Major General Mugisha
Muntu, Army Commander of Uganda People's Defense Forces.
</P>
<P>
This is the first gathering of defense chiefs in the post
independence history of East African (EA) countries.
</P>
<P>
The military chiefs also resolved establishment of a liaison
office for defence co-operation matters at the EA Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The meeting marks a turning point in the consolidation of the
co-operation now flourishing among the member states, said
Francis Muthaura, Executive Secretary of the East-African
Co-operation at the opening of the one-day session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
