NAIROBI, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Month-long clashes between
the Luo, Kisii, Kuria and Maasai tribes in Nyanza Province,
south-western Kenya, have left more than 20 people dead, charred
villages and caused a public panic.
</P>
<P>
At least 10 people from the Kisii community were hacked to
death in Kilgoris town, Trans Mara District Thursday, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
When word about the killings reached Gucha-Trans Mara border,
the Kisiis armed themselves with bows and arrows and proceeded to
Maasailand at Nyangusu where they seriously injured a number of
Maasais.
</P>
<P>
Rumors and leaflets warning "foreigners" were rampant in the
area where insecurity among local residents has been raging on as
brutal retaliation between different tribes appears to become
daily fare.
</P>
<P>
The root causes of the conflicts remain mysterious and have
been explained with matters ranging from buying and selling of
land, cattle rustling and the coming general elections.
</P>
<P>
Kisii District Commissioner Wilson Litole said the Thursday's
attack was aimed at scaring the Kisiis from participating in the
ruling KANU party nominations exercise which will be held next
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Across the border, pastoralist Maasai and Kurias have a
tradition of cattle rustling from each other and from Kisiis, who
in turn, have retaliated, leading to volatile relations between
the three tribes.
</P>
<P>
However, Luos and Maasais have lived in relative harmony since
a Migori-Transmara cross-border agreement three years ago. When
fighting erupted in Migori this time, Maasais joined Luos to
battle against Kisiis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
