<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arrhythmia Causes Sudden Death of Young </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 21 (Xinhua) -- An expert on cardiology has
said that 90 percent of the sudden death of people aged at 30-35
are caused by heart problems resulting from arrhythmia.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Cyprus Weekly published today, Antonio
Bayes de Luna, head of the International Society and Federation of
Cardiology, said that arrhythmia causes ventricular fibrillation,
and is usually brought on by the overgrowth of the ventrical
cavity which is usually a genetic disease.
</P>
<P>
De Luna is here to attend the three-day 16th international
cardiology conference due to be held today, at which he will
address difficult cases of arrhythmia.
</P>
<P>
He said that the coronary heart disease is the other major
killer of people at that age, which is caused by high cholesterol
levels, smoking and hypertension, and appears early in life.
</P>
<P>
This, too, may be affected by a genetic factor, he added.
</P>
<P>
Every year, there are 5-6 million people in the world dying
of heart diseases, according to De Luna.
</P>
<P>
He noted that heart-related diseases have been reduced in
developed countries due to preventive methods and also healthy
lifestyles, but they are on the rise in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
While rheumatic heart disease is still very common in
developing countries, it is effectively controlled with penicillin
in the developed world, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
