<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea to Seek IMF Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government
Friday said that it has decided to seek rescue loans from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) to lift itself out of a worst
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference later in the day, new Deputy Prime
Minister and Finance and Economy Minister Lim Chang-yuel confirmed
the decision but made it clear that formal loan request has yet to
be made.
</P>
<P>
"The government will make the final announcement on whether
Seoul will obtain an IMF loan or not in two to three days," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The tentative decision to resort to the IMF was reached after
talks between Minister Lim and IMF Vice President Stanley Fischer
in Seoul Friday.
</P>
<P>
The government has tried to secure loans from the central banks
of the United States and Japan, but failed to do so because they
said they would not extend loans unless Seoul first accepts IMF
bailout money.
</P>
<P>
The government Wednesday unveiled a desperate last-ditch
financial stabilization package. But it failed to prevent the
country from sliding further into financial turmoil. This may have
prompted the government to seek an IMF rescue money to bail out
the foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
The IMF's infusion of emergency bailout money into South Korea,
if implemented as planned, will surely result in a loss of
economic sovereignty and seismic upheavals of the national
economy, industry experts say.
</P>
<P>
"With the national economy managed by the IMF, the South Korean
people will have to endure all kinds of economic hardships,
including massive layoffs, freezing of wages, higher tax rates,
higher interest rates and extremely low GDP growth, among others,"
said a Seoul economist.
</P>
<P>
"Restructuring and M&AMP;As particularly among financial
institutions and automakers, opening of the local financial
market, and reforming the conglomerates-dominated economy will
also further accelerate, regardless of the intent of the
government and business communities," he asserted.
</P>
<P>
The IMF is expected to press South Korea for wider opening of
the financial market, mergers of less competitive financial
institutions and the automobile industry's restructuring as a
condition for extending a rescue package.
</P>
<P>
Despite the widespread pessimism, however, some experts raised
optimistic views, saying that the IMF rescue will help Seoul to
hasten the settlement of a set of previously thorny issues, such
as conglomerates' economic dominance, inflexibility in labor
market and financial-sector reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
