<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Take Measures to Keep Economy Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government is
planning a series of measures to ensure further economic growth
next year, Prime Minister Phan Van Khai said here today.
</P>
<P>
The measures include improving efficiency and competitiveness
among industries, developing agriculture toward industrialization
and modernization, and speeding up reforms at state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Phan Van Khai announced the planned new measures in his report
on the work of the government delivered at the second session of
the 10th National Assembly, or legislature, which opened today.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese economy has maintained the momentum of growth so
far this year but difficulties have emerged in keeping the pace
and sustainability of the growth, the prime minister noted.
</P>
<P>
The National Assembly's growth targets for this year's gross
domestic product (GDP), agricultural production, grain yields,
inflation and population expansion can be reached, he said.
</P>
<P>
A GDP growth of 9 percent is expected this year.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, growth rates for industrial production,
service sales and export turnover, estimated at 13, 9.5 and 20
percent respectively, will fall short of the targets.
</P>
<P>
During its current session, scheduled to last through December
10, the National Assembly will hear the government's plan on
economic and social progress for 1998, and its budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
Also on the review list of the legislature are priority
construction projects planned to be carried out over the next few
years, and the country's proposed Bank Law and some other bills.
</P>
</TEXT>
