<HEADLINE> 3,000 Residents Flee Conflict in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 21 (Xinhua) -- About 3,000 residents fled
their homes in North Cotabato province in the southern Philippines
due to tensions brought about by a series of skirmishes between
members of two Muslim groups.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency today reported that people abandoned
their homes for fear that they might be caught up in an impending
war between the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) and the Moro
Islamic Liberation Front (MILF).
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a breakaway faction of the mainstream MNLF which
signed a final peace agreement with the government in September
1996. The MILF, dissatisfied with the peace deal, demanded
separate peace talks and has signed a comprehensive ceasefire
agreement with Manila.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said some MNLF fighters killed in an ambush
three MILF rebels on their way to a feast near Pikit town on
November 16. In retaliation, the MILF staged an attack on an
MNLF-run village the next day, killing one MNLF member.
</P>
<P>
Government troops based in the nearby area took steps to stop
the conflict, using mortars to drive the MILF rebels away.
</P>
<P>
The evacuees are reportedly living with relatives in nearby
towns. They have appealed to government officials to look into
their problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
