<HEADLINE> Germany's Trade Surplus Surges to Nearly $54 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Germany's trade surplus surged to
93.9 billion marks (54 billion U.S. dollars) in the first nine
months of this year after another strong export showing in
September, the German Federal Statistics Office announced today.
</P>
<P>
The figures released today by the Wiesbaden-based office show
that Germany's exports continue its robust growth by expanding
23.1 percent over the level of a year ago to 78.5 billion marks
(45.1 billion dollars) in September.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports also increased by 15.2 percent to 63.7
billion marks (36.6 billion dollars), so that the country's
September trade surplus was 14.8 billion marks (8.5 billion
dollars) compared with 8.5 billion marks (4.9 billion dollars) a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
Taking the first nine months of 1997 as a whole, the country's
exports totalled 647.2 billion marks (372 billion dollars) against
an import total of 553 billion marks (318 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the country's current account balance, which also
includes trade in services, still registered a deficit of 7.5
billion marks (4.3 billion dollars) in the first nine months.
</P>
</TEXT>
