<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Silicone Breast Implants Will Leak, Scientists Warn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Scientists have found almost
all silicone breast implants will rupture and leak after 20 years,
a medical magazine here reported today.
</P>
<P>
A summary of research studies in The Lancet says only five
percent of women can expect to have both implants intact after 20
years, only 51 percent after 12 years and 89 percent after eight
years.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted on 592 implants which had been in place
for between one and 25 years. It recommended that implants be
removed after eight years. Mechanical testing of implants
confirmed that they become weaker as they age.
</P>
<P>
Researchers from the U.S. Food and Drug Administration say both
"the incidence and prevalence of breast implant rupture are much
higher than previously expected and the risk of rupture increases
as the implant ages."
</P>
<P>
Few of the ruptures were caused by obvious injury or
damage. Manufacturers of breast implants put rates of rupture at
0.2 to 1.1 percent although the U.S. government agency has
received higher estimates from other researchers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
