<HEADLINE> Mbeki to Visit Britain to Promot Bilateral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 21 (Xinhua) -- South African
Deputy-President Thabo Mbeki is due to visit Britain early next
Tuesday to solidify already strong diplomatic and trade
relations.
</P>
<P>
Local daily Business Day quoted diplomatic sources as
reporting today that Mbeki, who will be accompanied by Trade and
Industry Minister Alec Erwin, is due to meet Queen Elizabeth,
Primie Minister Tony Blair and Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
during his visit.
</P>
<P>
The sources said a British bid to supply all of South Africa's
new defense procurement needs will be high on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
This bid takes place in a highly competitive environment with
Germany, France, Spain, and Sweden among the European countries
also interested in selling arms to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The South African National Defense Force and defense ministry
are on record as having indicated that South Africa's procurement
needs include corvettes, tanks and aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The cost estimates have ranged from between two and three
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The importance of the current proposals is enhanced because of
suggestions about the establishment of an African peacekeeping
intervention force.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is likely to be an important part of such a
force. Local observers said that any country which arms South
Africa would be likely to gain influence in this body because of
the need for weapons and command standardization. 
</P>
