<HEADLINE> Zambian Banks Warned Against Money Laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's commercial banks have
been warned not to allow money laundering or face stiff
punishment.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner of the Drug Enforcement Committee (DEC) Raphael
Mungole issued the warning Thursday in Ndola, northern Zambia
when he opened the Institute of Bankers workshop on money
laundering.
</P>
<P>
He said that the serious threat posed by drug trafficking,
money laundering, corruption and organized crimes call for
special functions to be performed by the central and commercial
banks.
</P>
<P>
"Investment efforts in our country will require a financial
and banking sector whose top management levels are transparent.
As a commission, we will walk and speak a soft voice in banks but
at the same time apply a big stick on individuals who flout
banking regulations especially false returns to Bank of Zambia,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that banks should develop mechanisms for identifying
suspicious cash transactions apart from knowing their customers
well.
</P>
<P>
"A code of conduct embodied in an anti-money laundering
legislation is urgently required to strengthen administrative
vigilance in banks and detect those that connive with criminals,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged banks to support a government anti-money laundering
bill which the cabinet is still debating.
</P>
<P>
He said narcotic drug crime and money laundering do not only
have an insidious corrupting effect which stimulates the growth
of secondary underground economy, but that it also debilitates
the legitimate banking and financial sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
