<HEADLINE> Chinese Province Moves to Regulate Planning of Villages, Towns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The legislature of east
China's Zhejiang province has approved a regulation standardizing
the planning, construction and management of villages and towns in
the province.
</P>
<P>
The regulation, which will be effective on January 1, 1998,
says villages and towns will be built in a unified way so as to
reduce land waste, convenience the residents and protect the
environment, said officials in the Standing Committee of the
Zhejiang Provincial People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
As economy has developed rapidly, many villages and towns have
been built in Zhejiang in recent years, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
However, the construction of villages and towns lacked unified
planning, resulting in unreasonable distribution, insufficient
facilities and ill-advised use of farmland, they said.
</P>
<P>
Residents are being encouraged to invest in the construction of
villages and towns, according to the regulation.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also stipulates that residents in villages and
towns should plant trees around their houses and build garbage
disposal centers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
