<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Measures Urged to Protect Global Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Ecologists attending the
ongoing '97 China Environment Forum predict that the global
environment will be deteriorated if no major measures are
implemented.
</P>
<P>
Experts said today that the use of renewable resources -- land,
forest, fresh water, coastal areas, fisheries, and urban air -- is
beyond the resources' natural regeneration capacity and,
therefore, are unsustainable.
</P>
<P>
Suvit Yodmani, director and regional representative of the
United Nations Environment Program for the Asia-Pacific Region,
said that greenhouse gases are still being emitted at levels
higher than the stabilization target internationally agreed upon
under the U.N. Framework Convention on Climate Change.
</P>
<P>
The convention, passed in 1992, stipulates that the level of
greenhouse emissions in developed countries at the end of this
century should be reduced to 1990 levels.
</P>
<P>
Natural areas and the biodiversity they contain are diminishing
due to the expansion of agriculture and human settlements. Rapid,
unplanned urbanization, particularly in coastal areas, is putting
major stress on adjacent ecosystems, Yodmani said.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that the increasingly pervasive use and
spread of chemicals is causing major health risks, environmental
contamination and disposal problems.
</P>
<P>
Yodmani warned that continued reliance on hydrocarbons in the
energy sector to fuel economic development is clearly an
unsustainable practice.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the complex interactions among global biological,
geological and chemical cycles are leading to widespread ecosystem
damage and change including acidification, climate variability,
changes in hydrological cycles and the loss of
biodiversity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zzambia to Reclaim Infested Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior Zambian official has
said that there is urgent need to reclaim 33 percent of the
national land infested by tsetse flies, Times of Zambia reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Yotam Ngulube, deputy minister of agriculture, food and
fisheries, expressed his concern over the infested land Thursday
in Chilanga,20 kilometers south of the capital, while speaking at
the official handover of the European Union-constructed Regional
Tsetse Trypanosomiasis Control Program (RTTCP).
</P>
<P>
Ngulube said that the tsetse flies affect human life as well
as 25.percent of traditional herds of livestock throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
Large tracts of agricultural land are not accessible for
settlements or agricultural production as a result, said the
deputy minister, adding there is urgent need to open up these
areas in order to accommodate the ever expanding population and
to meet the nation's growing demand for food.
</P>
<P>
Ngulube stressed regional cooperation in eradicating the
tsetse flies.
</P>
<P>
He said that the 11-year old RTTCP which includs Malawi,
Mozambique, Zimbabwe and Namibia has addressed the tsetse fly and
disease problem beyond administrative boundaries.
</P>
<P>
At the handover ceremony, European Union resident
representative Charles Brook said Zambia, which got the largest
share of the 52 million U.S. dollars allotted to the RTTCP, is
the only one of the five countries that has produced its own
national strategic plan for the tsetse flies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Rejects Swazi's Territory Claim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Swaziland's claims to
her former territory in South Africa could never be entertained,
Home Affairs Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi, who is in Swaziland for a working visit, made the
remarks at a press conference in Mbabane airport, local media
reported.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi said the territory is now part of South Africa and
the issue of boundaries was settled long ago by an Organisation
of African Unity (OAU) charter, which recognized colonial
borders.
</P>
<P>
Swaziland, which wants a portion of South Africa's Mpumalanga
province transferred to the mountain kingdom, is signatory to the
charter, said Buthelezi.
</P>
<P>
There was no indication at the end of his visit that the
border issue had been discussed.
</P>
<P>
However, despite Buthelezi's statement and the OAU charter, a
six man border adjustment committee established by the late King
Sobhuza II following Swaziland's independence in 1989 to pursue
his country's century old claims to former Swazi territory in
South Africa, is still very active.
</P>
<P>
The committee, responsible to King Mswati III directly and
chaired by former home affairs minister Prince Khuzulwandle, is
still pursuing the border adjustment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
