<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Informal Businesses Dominate Mozambique's Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Over 90 per cent of the
Mozambican-Swazi trade is dominated by informal businesses, a
report said here today.
</P>
<P>
The report done by a U.S. Christian organization named "World
Vision", released the figure at a symposium on the informal trade
along the Mozambique and Swaziland border.
</P>
<P>
The informal businessmen, mainly those involved in small
businesses selling daily necessities, have provided people in the
two countries, especially the poorest people, with more adequate
food supply, and stabilized the prices, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Informal trade, according to the report, is also dominating
Mozambique's trade with other neighboring countries, like South
Africa, Zimbabwe, Zambia and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
But the report also said Mozambique has suffered an
unfavorable trade balance as most of its exports through the
informal businessmen are agricultural products, while most of its
imports are products with high additional value.
</P>
<P>
The report said that a value of 77.34 million U.S. Dollar of
the Mozambique's exports are agro-products, 57.65 million dollar
are of non-agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
Experts at the symposium urged that Mozambique encourage
agricultural production and recognize the role informal
businesses are playing at times when there are food crises in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Mozambique, Tanzania, Zambia, South
Africa, Swaziland and Malawi attended the symposium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
