<HEADLINE> Qian of China Meets Thai Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VANCOUVER, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Minister
Qian Qichen met his Thai counterpart Surin Pitsuwan here today and
hoped that elections in Cambodia will be held next May as
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Qian and Pitsuwan arrived here earlier in the day for the ninth
ministerial meeting of the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation
(APEC) forum which will open on Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Qian emphasized the importance to ensure
open and fair elections in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Expressing his hope that national reconciliation be achieved in
Cambodia, Qian said that King Norodom Sihanouk, highly respected
in the strife-torn country, plays an irreplaceable role.
</P>
<P>
Pitsuwan said Thailand was willing to make efforts for the
realization of Cambodia's national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed his appreciations for the diplomatic efforts
made by the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) in
resolving the Cambodian issues.
</P>
<P>
Qian also congratulated Pitsuwan for being appointed earlier
this month as the foreign minister, and said he believed Pitsuwan
will further push forward the relations between China and
Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
