<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Golf World Cup to Become Fourth Event on World Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The Golf World
Cup will become the fourth event on golf's world tour, the PGA
Tour commissioner Tim Finchem announced in South Carolina, the
United States on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to a news report,the announcement was made at the
43rd World Cup. The event was inaugurated in 1953 and will see
its last edition under the current format in 1999. Starting in
2000, it will be revamped to become part of the World Golf
Championships.
</P>
<P>
Finchem indicated that the current format of two-man teams from
32 nations playing four rounds of strokeplay is likely to be cut
but the resolution is yet to be finalized.
</P>
<P>
The event is likely to offer prize money around 4 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Finchem also said that the eligiblity might be changed to allow
more than one team from the stronger golfing nations to
participate. The comparably weaker nations would still have a
chance to qualify as well.
</P>
<P>
"The World Cup has a unique place in golf development around
the world," Finchem said, "We want to continue to utilize the
World Cup to develop that interest."
</P>
<P>
The World Golf Championships will begin in 1999 with three
events -- one matchplay and two strokeplay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0159 </DOCNO>
