<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
finished the week on a positive note, gaining almost one U.S. cent
in today's session as it was pushed higher by stronger Asian
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
The currency settled at 69.46 U.S. cents, from a close Thursday
of 68.61 and after reaching a high of 69.65 earlier in the
session.
</P>
<P>
Colonial State Bank senior foreign exchange trader Nick
Volanakis said profit-taking on short positions early in the
session saw a short squeeze upward.
</P>
<P>
Share markets in Australia, Tokyo and Hong Kong all lifted
today.
</P>
<P>
The news from South Korea, Australia's second largest trading
partner, was also better with the won trading higher as officials
confirmed they were talking with the International Monetary Fund
about a possible bailout package.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts reiterated that market sentiment toward the
Australian dollar remains on the downside amid the financial
crisis in Asia and fears that this will impact negatively on the
domestic economy.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was at 87.59 yen from 86.89 yen
previously and at 1.2003 marks from 1.1899 marks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
