<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Sharply Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
closed sharply higher today, as investors moved in on undervalued
stocks left artificially low in an atmosphere of volatile Asian
markets and slipping commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries closed 47.0 points higher at 2,481.7 after
opening strongly on the back of Wall Street gains overnight.
</P>
<P>
"I think the investors should be happy with the performance
today," said BNP Equities (Australia) broker John Bowie Wilson.
</P>
<P>
National turnover on the Australian market was 345.87 million
shares traded and valued at 664.33 million U.S. dollars, with
rises outnumbering falls by 607 to 467.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index was up 77.2 points to 4,224.0, while
the all resources index gained 23.3 points to 1,097.1.
</P>
<P>
Among the top traders was Telstra, whose installment receipts
finished their debut week up eight cents at 2.71 Australian
dollars. More than 83 million receipts were sold, valued at 149.89
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The National Australia bank rose strongly, up 45 cents at 19.95
Australian dollars, clawing back some ground lost Thursday when it
dipped after going ex-dividend.
</P>
<P>
The banking index jumped 117 points to 5,247.3, with the
Commonwealth bank firming 55.5 cents to 17.255 Australian dollars,
Westpac adding 22 cents to 9.07 Australian dollars and ANZ bank
lifting 19.6 cents to 10.186 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP shares recovered from a downbeat week that
saw investors deserting the stock for Telstra, up 64 cents to
13.80 Australian dollars on a turnover of 4.6 million shares.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was up 22 points to 937.6. Gold bullion in
Sydney was trading at 303.75 U.S. dollars an ounce, up from 303.50
U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
