<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Training System Being Tried Out In South China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, November 21 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong Province
will start a new labor training system in the next few months,
according to provincial Labor Department officials.
</P>
<P>
Zhongshan, Dongguan, Jiangmen, and Shantou cities have been
chosen for the pilot program to prepare the way for wider use by
April 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department has decided that employees should be
trained and get a certificate before they begin to work anywhere.
</P>
<P>
Poor people are allowed to pay tuition late or are exempt
from training fees, however, and workers can get subsidies during
their work-study programs.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the province says that employers should only
employ people with work certificates.
</P>
<P>
Officials say that the probation system will alleviate
unemployment in Guangdong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rice Cultivation on Sandy Lands Looks Promising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
successfully cultivated rice on the vast sandy lands of
northwestern China. With average per-hectare rice output reaching
more than 7,500 kilograms, the sandy lands have been turned into
high-yield farmland.
</P>
<P>
"We have grown rice on about 600 hectares of sandy lands, and
the techniques we applied will provide new means for sandy land
treatment," said Liu Xinming, director of the Lanzhou Institute of
Desert Research under the Chinese Academy of Sciences. Liu is
chief scientist for the research project.
</P>
<P>
"First, we pave a thin layer of plastic film at a certain depth
in sandy soil to prevent water and fertilizer from running
away. Then we make the land more productive by using special
fertilizers and water-saving irrigation techniques," Liu explained.
</P>
<P>
The institute began to test cultivation of rice on sandy lands
in 1992. Sites for testing included sandy land in Gansu Province
and the Ningxia Hui and Inner Mongolia autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
With improved techniques, the output of the "film-bottomed"
sandy fields has been two or three times as much as that of dry
farmland, and it is only 20 percent less than that of high-yield,
irrigated farmland.
</P>
<P>
China has vast areas of sandy land, with desert and
desertifiction land areas approaching 1.53 million square
kilometers, about 16 percent of the country's total land
area. Most of these lands are situated in Xinjiang, Gansu,
Ningxia, Shanxi and Inner Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
"Rice can be cultivated on millions of hectares of these sandy
lands. Besides, China has more than 200,000 square kilometers of
sandy land which can be irrigated through diversion works," Liu
said.
</P>
<P>
"With enough irrigation water, all of these sandy lands can be
cultivated with these techniques and turned into high-yield
farmland," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
