<HEADLINE> South Korea Formally Applies for IMF Rescue Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 21 (Xinhua) -- South Korea today formally
applied to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) for a rescue
package to bail out its plunging foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
Government officials said the application was filed with IMF
Vice President Stanley Fisher, now on a visit here.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, a member of the Washington-based IMF, applied for
about 50 billion U.S. dollars, which might be provided by other
IMF members including the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The country earlier refused to seek IMF assistance, which
requires economic structural reforms, despite recent serious
financial crisis similar to those hitting Southeast Asia. 
</P>
