<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Ratifies SADC Transport Protocol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's parliament on
Thursday ratified the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) protocol which seeks to establish uniform transport,
communications and meteorology systems that provide efficient
uniform operations in the region.
</P>
<P>
The protocol on transport, communications and meteorology was
signed by SADC heads of states and government in August 1996.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean transport and energy deputy minister Zenso Nsimbi
said the protocol would promote economic and social development
while being environmentally and economically sustainable.
</P>
<P>
The protocol was an international legal instrument meant to
acquire domestic legal force in the law of each member state.
</P>
<P>
"The protocol expresses the commitment of SADC member-states
to cooperate in collectively addressing pertinent matters and
priority issues within the transport, communications and
meteorology sectors from a regional perspective," said Nsimbi.
</P>
<P>
Nine sub-sectors including integrated transport, road
infrastructure, road transport and road traffic, maritime and
inland waterway transport, railways, civil aviation,
telecommunications, postal services and meteorology are covered
under the protocol.
</P>
<P>
Nsimbi said Zimbabwe had gone a long way in resolving some of
the issues raised in the protocol in that all towns, mines,
tourist areas and rural service centres were connected by
surfaced roads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
