<HEADLINE> L'Oreal Picks Movie Star to Be China Spokeswoman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 21 (Xinhua) -- L'Oreal, the world's largest
multinational cosmetics manufacturer in Paris, announced here
Wednesday that Chinese movie star Gong Li would be the company's
image in China.
</P>
<P>
A billboard featuring Gong was unveiled by L'Oreal President
and CEO Lindsay Owen-Jones at the Bands of Shanghai, China's
largest financial center. The billboard, 40 meters long and 15
meters high, is the largest on China's inland areas.
</P>
<P>
Owen-Jones said he was happy to see that L'Oreal has a new home
and a new face in China.
</P>
<P>
L'Oreal's business in China is growing faster than any of its
other markets in the world, according to Owen-Jones.
</P>
<P>
In February of 1997, L'Oreal (China) Company was founded in
Shanghai to provide Chinese customers with skin cream, hair-care
products, make-up and perfume.
</P>
<P>
Gong's image will appear at L'Oreal counters in department
stores of China's major cities, Owen-Jones said, and people all
over China will be able to see her in L'Oreal's television
advertisements.  
