<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Indian Government Faces New Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government is
facing new challenges as the Congress party threatened on Thursday
to withdraw support to the United Front (UF) coalition headed by
Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral unless a coalition partner was
ousted from the government.
</P>
<P>
Congress party President Sitaram Kesri on Thursday in a terse
letter asked the prime minister to choose between the Congress and
the Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam (DMK), a partner in the United Front
coalition.
Earlier in the day, a report tabled by a commission in both
houses of Parliament said the DMK was linked with the
assassination of former prime minister Rajiv Gandhi in 1991.
Kesri said in his letter, "The Congress Working Committee (CWC),
the highest policy-making body of the party, has decided that it
cannot continue to extend its support to the United Front
Government if the DMK continues to be a constituent of the
government in view of the indictment by the Jain Commission
report, tabled in both Houses of Parliament today."
</P>
<P>
The Congress actually sounded a death knell for the government
as it was the main supporter of the Gujral coalition.
</P>
<P>
Senior Congress leader Pranab Mukherjee told a press conference
Thursday that serious consequences would follow if the indictments
were not acted upon.
</P>
<P>
The angry Congress stalled proceedings in both houses of
Parliament to demand the DMK's ouster from the government and
forced the sessions to be adjourned for the day.
</P>
<P>
The core committee of the UF is expected to meet here this
morning to consider the response to Kesri's letter. Though the
letter did not set any deadline, it evidently expected an
immediate reply from the prime minister to the crucial question of
choosing between the DMK and the Congress.
</P>
<P>
In late March this year, the UF government headed by its first
prime minister D. Gowda fell due to the withdrawal of support by
the Congress. The Gujral government is still a minority government
in Parliament and it will face a similar fate if the Congress
repeats its March action.
</P>
<P>
DMK leader M. Karunanidhi on Thursday described the allegation
against his party as "politically motivated" and said it was
unacceptable. He added that there was no valid reason for DMK
ministers to quit.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), the
country's biggest opposition party and the largest group in the
lower house of parliament, was out to fish in the troubled waters
by playing its card both inside and outside Parliament.
</P>
<P>
On the floor of the House, it pressed for tabling the Jain
Commission report and insisted on having a discussion on it.
Outside Parliament, it reiterated that its doors were open for
those wishing to avert a mid-term election. The BJP said that it
was keeping all its options open and would try to form a
government at the center if the Congress withdrew support to the
Gujral government.
</P>
<P>
There are several possibilities under the current
circumstances: the Gujral government drops the DMK and continues
to get support from the Congress; the Gujral government rejects
Congress' demand and falls; the BJP forms the government with the
support of other parties; or Parliament is dissolved and polls are
held. No matter which possibility occurs, the country's fluid
political situation will continue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA moves to address food shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lusaka, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern
and Southern Africa (COMESA) has embarked on a program to address
the expected food shortage in the 1998/99 season.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail today quoted COMESA acting secretary general
Erastus Mwencha as saying here today that it will meet the World
Food Program next month to work out a strategy to address the
food shortage due to low rainfall arising from the El Nino
occurrence this year.
</P>
<P>
He said with proper coordination among COMESA member countries
it will be able to generate constant supplies of food all year
round.
</P>
<P>
"This is why we propose to establish free trade in
agricultural products in COMESA in 1999. You will also be
pleasantly surprised to learn that most member states already
have a zero or low tariff on agriculture commodities," he said.
</P>
<P>
El Nino is a climatical pattern that has brought about a dry
spell in the southern part of Africa with little or no rain in
some places. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. African Military Chiefs Meet over Common </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Top military chiefs from
Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania held talks Thursday over common
defence in the three East African Cooperation (EAC) member
states, the Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's Chief of General Staff General Daudi Tonje, Chief of
Tanzania People's Defence Forces General R.P. Mboma and Army
Commander of Ugandan People's Defence Forces General Mugisha
Muntu attended the meeting in northern Tanzanian town Arusha.
</P>
<P>
This is the first meeting of its kind in the post-independence
history of the three countries.
</P>
<P>
The meeting agreed on a draft memorandum of understanding
recommended for the three governments. It proposed a deepening of
cooperation in defence among them, including exchange visits,
joint training and security, disaster handling and coordination
of other defence-related matters.
</P>
<P>
The military leaders also proposed to establish an institution
in charge of advancing defence cooperation, including a liaison
office at the EAC secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they called for rapid progress towards political
unity in the EAC region.
</P>
<P>
"The goal of the Cooperation ought to be the political union
of the three countries and the attainment of that goal today
would not be too soon for us," said Gel. Tonje.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session, EAC Executive Secretary
Francis Muthaura said the meeting marked a turning point in the
consolidation of the cooperation now flourishing in all three
countries.
</P>
<P>
There are many areas in which the defence forces of the three
states could cooperate, he said.
</P>
<P>
"With assured and durable security, the people of EA (East
Africa) should have the necessary enabling environment to
maximize the utilization of their talents," he concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
