<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. space shuttle Columbia's astronauts Thursday
delayed releasing a satellite that observes the sun because of
spacecraft problems, the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration (NASA) said.
</P>
<P>
NASA ordered the crew to wait until Friday before launching the
Spartan satellite from the spacecraft for a two-day-flight.
</P>
<P>
The suspension was ordered after NASA found voltage problems
with Soho, another solar observatory.
</P>
<P>
Soho shut itself down just hours before Columbia blasted off
Wednesday. Ground controllers had the two-year-old observatory
back in operation Thursday evening. (U.S.-Satellite-Put Off)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUDAPEST -- The Hungarian government Thursday gave official
recognition to the majority of voters who recently approved of
NATO membership.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the National Assembly on the final result of the
referendum held last Sunday, Kukorelli Istvan, chief of the
national election commission, said among the 49 percent of eight
million eligible voters who took part in the referendum, 85
percent voted for Hungary's entry into the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO). (Hungary-Referendum-Announcement) 
</P>
</TEXT>
