<HEADLINE> Six Chinese Firms Targeted for Top 500 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 21 (Xinhua) -- China's Central Government will
support six big enterprises in a bid to elevate them into the
ranks of the world's top 500 firms by 2010, "China Daily" reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Li Rongrong, Vice-minister in charge of the State Economic and
Trade Commission, was quoted by the English newspaper as saying
that the government plans to invest 20 million yuan (2.41 million
US dollars) annually to each of the six firms for technological
advancement.
</P>
<P>
The six firms are Shanghai Baoshan Iron and Steel Company,
electric appliance maker Haier Group in east China's Shandong
province, color television giant Changhong Electric Co (Group) in
west Sichuan province, North China Pharmaceutical (Group) Co in
Hebei province, Jiangnan Shipyard co in Shanghai and computer
producer Founder Group in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The companies, some having subsidaries aboard, will try to
uplift their annual investment in technology development to five
to ten percent of their total sales revenue. The national average
now stands at a meagre one percent. 
</P>
