<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qinghai Farmers Want Fewer Children for Economic Reasons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Qinghai's many farmers and
herdsmen are reaping financial benefits for limiting the size of
their families.
</P>
<P>
More and more farmers and minority people in this northwestern
province, consisting of the Han ethnical group and 42 different
minorities, willingly gave up their rights to favorable family
planning rules.
</P>
<P>
According to provincial rules, Han people who reside in
agricultural or pastoral areas are entitled to two children while
minority people can have three. However, most city dwellers can
have only one child.
</P>
<P>
China, which has one-fifth of the world's population, has
offered financial inducements to farmers to encourage fewer
children.
</P>
<P>
Ulan County has granted child-health subsidies and bought
old-age insurance policies for families who comply with family
planning rules.
</P>
<P>
Qinghai has poured a total of 18.8 million yuan (2.26 million
U.S. dollars) into helping 20,000 poor families hold down
population growth, said Han Yugui, an official of the Provincial
Family Planning Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Oldest Map Discovered by Huang Yan and Yang Xinhe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Archeologists have
discovered a 2,300-year-old map clearly marked with distances in
north China's Hebei Province. It is believed to be the oldest map
of its kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
The map was carved into a 96-cm-long, 48-cm wide and 0.8-cm
thick copper plate and includes a drawing of the royal mausoleums
of Wang Cuo (344-313 B.C.), the fifth king of Zhongshan Kingdom,
one of dozens of principalities in the epoch of warring states
(475-221 B.C.).
</P>
<P>
"It is not only the oldest map ever found in China but the
oldest map noted with numerals in the world," said Du Naisong, a
researcher with the Palace Museum located in Beijing's Forbidden
City.
</P>
<P>
The map, known as "Zhao Yu Tu" in Chinese, has been identified
by connoisseurs of cultural artifacts led by Du as a national
treasure.
</P>
<P>
Du is leading a group from China's major museums doing
appraisal work on cultural relics in Hebei. They believe Zhao Yu
Tu is important in the study of historic maps of China and the
world.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Yu Tu was unearthed from an underground palace of an
imperial mausoleum in Pingshan County, Hebei in the late 1970s. It
was not until recently that experts determined the special
historic value of the map.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Yu Tu marks locations of buildings in five mausoleums of
Wang, his queen and concubines. It also specifies halls, palaces
and gates of the mausoleums with words and graphic symbols.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-three places are marked with words and 38 places are
marked with symbols on the map. Symbols, numerals and epigraphs on
the map are inlaid with pure gold and silver. Lines, characters
and numerals at the central part of the map are in gold, while the
peripheral characters and lines are in silver.
</P>
<P>
Unlike modern maps, directions indicated on Zhao Yu Tu are with
the south on the top and the north at the bottom, said Zhang
Pingyi, a researcher from Hebei Museum, who reckoned the scale of
the map is approximately one cm to five meters.
</P>
<P>
Zhang's points have also been supported by historian Li Xueqin,
director of the Institute of History under the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences and Fu Sinian and Yang Hongxun, who are both
renowned archeologists in China.
</P>
<P>
The experts said that graph, symbol, scale, location, longitude
and latitude are key elements of a map. Zhao Yu Tu has these
elements except longitude and latitude, according to the
historians.
</P>
<P>
Also found on Zhao Yu Tu is a 42-character imperial edict of
the king. The edict was written in Jin Wen, an ancient language
used during the epoch of warring states. It has taken experts on
ancient languages a long time to interpret the edict.
</P>
<P>
The edict is an order from King Wang Cuo for the building of
his mausoleum. The king asked for two copies of Zhao Yu Tu, one to
be stored by the imperial court of Zhongshan Kingdom and the other
to be buried with the king.
</P>
<P>
The one discovered in Pingshan County was buried with the
king. Archeologists have no idea where the other copy is, or if it
still exists.
</P>
<P>
Zhongshan Kingdom (506-295 B.C.) was founded in today's central
and southern part of Hebei by the Xianyu ethnic minority
inhabitants of northern China.
</P>
<P>
The ancient kingdom was very advanced in smelting and copper,
according to experts who have studied more than 10,000 cultural
artifacts unearthed from the Zhongshan king's tomb.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
