<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gansu's Ethnic Economy Booming (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Gansu Province in northwestern
China has 44 ethnic groups who are leaving remote mountainous
regions to help speed up the area's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
As a compact community site for the Hui ethnic group, Linxia
used to be a remote and economically backward region in Gansu. But
now one in every five local residents are engaged in
transportation or processing businesses.
</P>
<P>
Long-distance transportation teams consisting of Hui, Tibetan,
Dongxiang and Shala ethnic groups frequently travel the line
linking Qinghai and Tibet. They transport local products, daily
items and fashionable clothes made in coastal regions to Tibet and
bring back Tibetan-made artwork and medicinal herbs.
</P>
<P>
Hui business people from Linxia can be found peddling in almost
every large coastal city in southeast China. Some Linxia farmers
set up joint ventures at Tibet's border markets with businessmen
from neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
With more frequent economic exchanges going on, a group of
booming markets have emerged from the province's ethnic
regions. The products from the Longshan market in Zhangjiachuan
Hui Autonomous County have been sold to member countries of the
Commonwealth of Independent States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
