<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exposed Stalagmite Relics Found in Hebei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists and
scientists have found ancient stalagmite relics on a hilltop in
Lincheng County, north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists say the find, the first of its kind, is a
marvelous natural phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
Song Linhua, professor from the Institute of Geophysics under
the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS), and a group of scientists
stumbled across the 500-square meter stalagmite ruins while doing
field work near a cave.
</P>
<P>
Initially shaped 500 million years ago, the cave under the
stalagmite sprawl has five halls, the largest measuring 2,470
square meters, and more than 150 scenic spots.
</P>
<P>
The recent find provides important scientific information on
the land forms of the Taihang Mountains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Develops Hydro-Electric Power Resources (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 21 (Xinhua) -- This is the time for China to
exploit its hydro-electric power resources, and a major step was
taken on October 28 when the Yellow River was dammed for the
construction of the Xiaolangdi water control project in Henan
Province.
</P>
<P>
six 300,000-kw generators will be installed at Xiaolangdi and
they will generate 5.1 billion kwh of electricity a year when the
project is completed.
</P>
<P>
Then, on November 8, damming of China's longest Yangtze River
for the construction of the multi-purpose dam at the Three Gorges
was completed. The dam will be the biggest of its kind in the
world, and its 26 generators will be able to generate 84.6 billion
kwh of electricity a year, 13 billion kwh more than the Itaipu
power station in South America, presently the world's largest.
</P>
<P>
In a recent speech, Premier Li Peng called for increasing
hydro-electric power's share of the country's power from 25
percent now to 30 percent by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the Chinese Government places greater importance
on developing hydro-electric power resources has brought
opportunities for China's minor rivers like the Lancang in the
southwest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Develops Hydro-Electric Power Resources (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Lancang River starts in the Tangula Mountains in Qinghai
Province and its name changes to the Mekong after it enters into
Southeast Asia. The 2,000-km river in China has vast
hydro-electric power potential and is a national hydro-electric
power development base. Plans call for 14 power stations with a
combined capacity of 22 million kw.
</P>
<P>
Diverse financing is providing the capital needed, You Wanlong,
manager of the Yunnan Dachaoshan Hydropower Co. Ltd. told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Work on the Dachaoshan Power Station began with damming
completed on November 10. It will cost 8.87 billion yuan, which
will come from the State Development and Investment Corp. and
three Yunnan companies. The State Development Bank has decided to
provide more than four billion yuan in loans.
</P>
<P>
The Asia Development Bank will also provide 100 million
U.S. dollars in loans to finance construction of Dachaoshan, which
is the second dam on the Lancang. The first is at Manwan and now
generates 5.9 billion kwh of electricity a year.
</P>
<P>
The Dachaoshan project will be able to generate 7 billion kwh
of electricity a year when completed in 2003. Its first generator
is scheduled to go online in 2001.
</P>
<P>
Downstream, the Jinghong Hydro-electric Power Station, which
will have a capacity of 1.5 million kw, will get backing from
Thailand and will mainly supply power to that country. Feasibility
studies for the project were completed recently.
</P>
<P>
Design work for the Xiaowan Station upstream, a key project for
developing resources on the Lancang, has been completed. The
station has an installed capacity of 4.2 million kw and will need
40 billion yuan.  It will be able to generate 19 billion kwh of
electricity a year when completed and will help other stations to
generate an extra seven billion kwh of electricity annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
