<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Textbooks to Include Tax Information </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The State Education Commission
has announced that, for the first time, it will include tax
information in primary and high school textbooks.
</P>
<P>
A commission official said the move will enable Chinese
citizens to become familiar with finance at an early age.
</P>
<P>
Jin Xuefang, deputy director of the Basic Education Department
of the commission, said taxes are a major source of government
revenue and the foundation for educational development.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese misunderstand the system and become tax dodgers,
he said, adding that it is necessary to educate children about
taxes.
</P>
<P>
A group of experts will discuss the feasibility of tax concepts
in language, mathematics and ethics textbooks.
</P>
<P>
China has 136 million primary school students and 49.7 million
middle school students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
