<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy to Take Measures Against Pedophilia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government will take
measures to protect children following revelation of several
pedophilia cases a week ago, said Italian Minister for Social
Solidarity Livia Turco here today.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the measures would begin with the
introduction of sex education starting from elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
"The first center-left government intends to discuss it calmly
to arrive at a law in a matter of days," she said.
</P>
<P>
Proposals for introducing sex education in schools were
routinely turned down by the Christian Democrats who controlled
Italian politics for decades until the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Besides sex education, school teachers will be trained on how
to spot signs of child abuse on December 19 in Naples.
</P>
<P>
The government also supports increasing penalties against
convicted pedophiles, the minister said, but preventing the abuses
is more important than making punishment more harsh.
</P>
<P>
A nine-year-old Italian boy was killed last Friday, his body
burned, by a family friend in an attempt to prevent the boy from
telling his parents about years of sexual abuse, authorities
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
