<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water shortage Hits Bangladesh's Northern Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 11 (Xinhua) -- The navigation and irrigation
network in the northern region of Bangladesh are being greatly
hampered due to an abnormal fall in the water level of all the
rivers and tributaries of the region.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources from the Agriculture Extension
Department here today, about 600,000 hectares of standing rice
crops in the region are experiencing acute irrigation crisis which
may lead to 30-40 percent reduction of the crops.
</P>
<P>
Due to adverse effect of the Farakka Barrage, the water level
of the Padma, Atrai, Barnoi, Gur Nondakuga, Karotia and Teesta and
other water bodies connecting with the Padma in the region have
fallen to a record mark this season, the sources stated, adding as
a result, the irrigation system had collapsed, and the navigation
in those river routes had been also affected seriously.
</P>
<P>
Of 113 tributaries of the Padma and Jamuna, only 40 can provide
irrigation facilities to the crop fields in this winter season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Frozen Food Industry Finding Its Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Frozen food is becoming an
increasingly popular consumer item in China, but the industry is
still searching for ways to develop.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, China produced more than eight million
tons of frozen food, some of it exported to Japan, Southeast Asia,
and Europe, but, in spite of its huge development potential, there
are still problems that hinder development.
</P>
<P>
China's frozen food industry needs greater variety and more
brand-name and lower-priced products, according to today's Market
Daily.
</P>
<P>
Most Chinese frozen foodstuffs are sold to urbanites, but
buyers are limited to less than a dozen varieties of frozen
dumplings and steamed bread on the racks of major department
stores, chain stores, or small shops.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the price, quality, and nutritional value of most
frozen foods are unsatisfactory, something that experts say is
because of the rush to get involved by some medium-sized and small
enterprises that have inadequate facilities and technology.
</P>
<P>
The market is huge but not well explored in China. The
country's fast food industry, where frozen food is important, is
increasing at an annual rate of 20 percent, and its sales account
for a fourth of total of the food industry.
</P>
<P>
Some experts predict that frozen foods will account for 60
percent of the total food consumption worldwide in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Allows Auctioning of Hazardous Waste </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 21 (Xinhua) -- India's Ministry of
Environment and Forests has allowed the auctioning of a stockpile
of uncleared imported hazardous waste, The Observer of Business
and Politics reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The stockpile has been lying at the Inland Container Depot at
Tughlaqabad in the capital since 1995.
</P>
<P>
Greenpeace has revealed in its investigations that more than
100 containers of hazardous and potentially hazardous wastes
including battery scrap, zinc ash, lead ash and waste oil are
stockpiled at the Inland Container Depot in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
"Our fear is that these illegally imported wastes may now find
their way to waste processing facilities around the country
because of the reported government decision," said Nityanand
Jayaraman of Greenpeace.
</P>
<P>
After the Supreme Court in the country banned imports of
hazardous waste in May 1997, an expert committee was appointed by
the court to study the hazardous waste situation in the country
and recommended a management plan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
