<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Information Technology Important to Asian Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN FRANCISCO, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Asia's recovery from its
financial markets turmoil lies in new ways of doing business, a U.S.
business executive said here today at an international conference.
</P>
<P>
Opening the two-day Asia-Pacific Information Technology Summit
in San Francisco, Intel CEO Andy Grove, who chairs the meeting,
said that integrating global commerce is a factor right now in
Asia's financial crisis. In this view, the most important effect
of connectivity via PCs is that it reduces the minimum scale for
business to get into the game, he said.
</P>
<P>
A tool that makes sellers more efficient and buyers more
knowledgeable is a very effective economic infrastructure in a
society, Grove said in an interview with local press prior to the
conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference is sponsored by the Pacific Economic Cooperation
Council, a business-based organization that helps formulate policy
initiatives for the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum (APEC).
</P>
<P>
The U.S. expenditures on exploiting Internet-based commerce are
three times the percentage of GDP of the Asian economies, Grove
said.
</P>
<P>
Pushing for more investment in connected computers and in
Internet commerce, Grove said that the world will have one billion
connected computers sometime in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
"The figure represents 15-20 percent of the world's population
and the greatest opportunity for countries on the Pacific Rim,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from integrating global commerce, Grove mentioned health
care and education as two other major problems that Asia is
facing. He said that computer connectivity can reach each of these
problems.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the policies he wants to promote at the
conference, which is attended by more than 500 industry leaders
and government officials, Grove said, "I am advocating one
policy: embrace information technology because your future depends
on it."
</P>
<P>
"It is a belief that technology can be a solution as compared
to a belief that technology is a luxury," said Grove. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
