<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Air TV Series on Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Faced with scientific
breakthroughs such as the cloning of sheep and the exploration of
life on Mars, Chinese media workers are preparing to tackle the
science revolution with a 36-part TV series.
</P>
<P>
"Life," adapted from Japanese NHK, will be aired by the Beijing
Television Station starting this weekend with the support of the
China Association for Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
The program will tell Chinese audiences about the mystery of
life and how China can avoid isolation from the modern scientific
revolution, especially gene engineering, producer Zeng Tao said.
</P>
<P>
She said the program will use computerized three-dimensional
technology to duplicate four billion years of history during which
life was born and evolved into human beings.
</P>
<P>
The program will reveal stunning stories such as that the
dinosaur was not killed by a meteorite 65 million years ago but by
beautiful flowers and that Darwin's theory of evolution already
is outmoded.
</P>
<P>
Problems faced by modern people will be discussed along with
the future of our small planet, Zeng said.
</P>
<P>
The TV station will produce more scientific programs, including
"Universe," "Digital Times" and "Human Brain" to echo the
government's call to rejuvenate the country through science and
technology.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese media have increased their coverage of science.
For example, China Central Television earlier this year replaced a
prime-time show on local scenery with a popular science
program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
