<HEADLINE> Chinese Village Elections Attract Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Grass-roots elections in
the villages of China's Hebei province have made quite an
impression on foreign visitors, according to the provincial civil
affairs department.
</P>
<P>
Visitors from the United States and Europe say they regard the
election as a form of democracy in rural China. The village
committee, which is the most basic form of power, has gone through
the fourth reshuffling this year, and 96 percent of Hebei's
villages have finished elections.
</P>
<P>
Visitors from 20 foreign countries witnessed a few of
elections. James Sasser, U.S. Ambassador to China, also showed his
interest in village election during a rural visit in May.
</P>
<P>
Walter Nocker, minister of the German Embassy in Beijing, said,
"China has a good form of democracy, particularly the grass-roots
elections in rural areas."
</P>
<P>
"Those villagers organized the elections fairly well," said
Paul Peters, a diplomat from the Netherlands. 
</P>
