<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> River Polluters Face 40-Day Deadline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 21 (Xinhua) -- All 1,500 polluters along the
Huaihe River, one of the five major rivers in China, face
compulsory shutdowns if they fail to meet national standards
before December 31, an official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Chinese authorities have compelled those businesses, each with
more than 100 tons of annual wastewater emissions, to stop
polluting the river. The Huaihe River flows through Anhui, Shandong,
Henan and Jiangsu provinces, and its basin extends for 270,000
square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government will not waver in forcing the overhaul
of the 1,500 polluting businesses, said Zang Yuxiang, deputy
director of the Pollution Control Department under the National
Environmental Protection Agency (NEPA). Zang's remarks came at the
1997 China Environment Forum.
</P>
<P>
China's national plan for water pollution control stipulates
that all sources of industrial pollution in the river basin must
meet emission standards and that by 2000 the water quality in the
river's trunk, lakes and reservoirs should meet the requirements.
</P>
<P>
Last year's shutdown of nearly 5,000 small businesses reduced
river pollution by 25 percent. These stern measures by the
government and the December 31 deadline should reduce pollution
levels by another 30 percent, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1990s, deterioration of the Huaihe River's water
quality has been astounding, Zang said. Yearly emissions of 2.4
billion tons of wastewater seriously polluted drinking water
sources and caused heavy loss to industrial and agricultural
production, Zang said.
</P>
<P>
Wastewater from small paper mills and breweries are responsible
for more than 70 percent of the problem, he said.
</P>
<P>
China has appropriated 1.3 billion yuan (about 160 million
U.S. dollars) to reduce pollution in the river. World Bank loans
worth 400 million U.S. dollars also supported the clean-up of the
Huaihe River Basin, Zang said.
</P>
<P>
The most recent statistics show that 525 severe polluters have
met the required standards.
</P>
<P>
The river basin, an important grain and cotton production area,
covers 35 percent of the country and has a population of 150
million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
