<HEADLINE> Thailand to Speed up Repatriation of Illegal Aliens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 21 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will speed up
repatriation of illegal aliens now under detention, a senior Thai
immigration official said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 illegal aliens will be sent back to their countries
by December 5 as the immigration authorities can no longer to
afford to feed them due to the country's budget constraints, said
Police Lt. Gen. Chidchai Vanasatidya of the Immigration Bureau
under the Royal Thai Police Department.
</P>
<P>
In future, illegal aliens would be allowed to stay for no more
than four days at some detention centers, Chidchai was quoted as
saying by today's local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Currently, at least 800,000 aliens, mostly from Myanmar and
Cambodia, are working in Thailand, he said, adding only about
351,000 of them are registered with the authorities.
</P>
<P>
From January to October this year, the Immigration Bureau has
repatriated 93,172 illegal alien workers, compared to 25,358 for
the same period last year, the officer said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year, the number of aliens repatriated is
expected to reach 100,000, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
