<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Doubts Power of Landmine Ban Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 21 (Xinhua) -- An Indonesian official has
stated that the Ottawa Treaty on Landmines will probably not
significantly reduce the number of landmines in the world.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a symposium here Thursday, Directorate for
International Organizations of the Foreign Ministry Hasan Kleib
said that the treaty on the total ban of landmines will be signed
by 104 countries, including Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
He added that "but most of those countries are small states,
such as Fiji, Samoa, Togo and others. And the big countries such
as the United States will not sign it. So how can we expect a
significant reduction?"
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has decided to attend the Ottawa conference on
December 2-4 to Sign the convention on the banning of
anti-personnel landmines.
</P>
<P>
There are at least 110 million landmines scattered in 60
countries around the world, mostly in Afghanistan, Angola, Bosnia,
Cambodia, Mozambique and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Small countries only posses a small number of landmines, and
even if they are eliminated, the world will still posses a great
number of landmines, sources at the Foreign Ministry today quoted
Hasan as saying.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that there are more than 250,000 people around
the world who have been blown up by landmines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
