<HEADLINE> Lower Aussie Dollar Helps Keep Wool Prices Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The lower Australian dollar
helped keep wool prices unusually stable at this week's sales, the
Australian Council of Wool Exporters (ACWE) said today.
</P>
<P>
The eastern market indicator rose two cents to close the week
at 710 Australian cents (487 U.S. cents) a clean kilogram while
the western market indicator remained unchanged at 649 cents (445
U.S. cents).
</P>
<P>
About 47,833 bales were offered, with a pass-in rate of 6.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
"The wool market has displayed an unusual degree of stability
in recent weeks with auction prices moving only marginally on
average at sales in (the two Australian cities of) Goulburn and
Geelong this week," the council said in its weekly wool market
review.
</P>
<P>
"The level of the Australian dollar relative to the major
buying currencies continues to be a very positive factor and is
helping to maintain widespread competition from local processors
and most of the major overseas traders."
</P>
<P>
Sales continue next week in Sydney, Melbourne and Fremantle
with a relatively large offering of 116,700 bales rostered.
</P>
