<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Supreme Court Takes up Petition Challenging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 21 (Xinhua) -- A three-member bench of the
Supreme Court of Pakistan, headed by Chief Justice Sajjad Ali
Shah, will take up a petition today challenging the 13th Amendment
to the constitution, informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
The 13th Amendment, which was passed by the parliament in April
this year, took away the powers of the president to dissolve the
National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the petition against the 13th Amendment
was not on today's case list of the apex court.
</P>
<P>
According to the original schedule, the first case to be taken
up by the court today is the contempt petition against Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif and 11 other respondents.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday night, however, Sajjad ordered the court officials
to place the petition challenging the 13th Amendment on today's
list and it will be heard before the petition against the prime
minister, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
If the court upholds the petition against the 13th Amendment,
the controversial article 58 (2b), under which the president has
the powers to dissolve the National Assembly, will be restored,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The decision of the Supreme Court to take up the petition today
came only one day after the parliament was reportedly planning to
impeach the president because he was reluctant to sign the amended
contempt of court bill.
</P>
<P>
The bill was passed by the parliament on Tuesday tending to
give protection to Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif in the ongoing case
of contempt against him in the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
Under the Constitution of Pakistan, the president has 30 days
to assent the bill.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Sharif urged President Farooq Leghari to sign the
bill into law to end the prevailing political crisis in the
country.
</P>
<P>
But the Supreme Court on Thursday passed an interim order
asking the president not to assent the bill.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
