<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central, East European Nations Launch No Smoking Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Central and Eastern European
nations today launched a no-smoking campaign and are calling on
people to give up smoking.
</P>
<P>
There is a large number of smokers in Central and Eastern
Europe, Romanian news agency ROMPRES quoted a poll result as
reporting.
</P>
<P>
In Germany, 12 percent of adults smoke. In Romania, the
proportion is 42.7 percent and 29 percent in the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
In addition, more and more minors and women are beginning to
smoke in Romania, said the report, adding that the percentage of
women smokers is 32.8 percent and 15.2 percent in the Czech
Republic.
</P>
<P>
Some experts attribute the reasons to the opening of regional
markets to Western tobacco companies and the weak control of
Central and East European countries on this matter, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
The third Thursday of November has been designated as
"International No Smoking Day" in the region, the report added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
