<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computers With a Human Ear Demonstrated at Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAS VEGAS, November 20 (Xinhua) -- If you suffer repetitive
stress syndrome, or are a "professional word user" such as
lawyers, writers and doctors, then you probably have a wish when
using computers.
</P>
<P>
A voice-operated computer, which only requires voice commands
to operate could be the answer to your prayers.
</P>
<P>
Voice recognition has until now been plagued by inaccuracy in
translating voices to text on a computer screen, and lack of
intelligence in distinguishing between homonyms.
</P>
<P>
However, at the Comdex computer show, a few firms including
Lernout &AMP; Hauspie, Dragon Systems and IBM, are introducing
software that brings the dream closer to reality.
</P>
<P>
In preview demonstrations this week, Voice Xpress created an
on-screen letter dictated in a normal speaking voice. It also
performed editing functions such as bold-facing and italicizing
words or phrases and indenting paragraphs, all through oral
commands. It could color highlight words it was not sure about and
give an author a quick review.
</P>
<P>
The ultimate aim is to make households without computers buy
them by enabling people to talk to their computers.
</P>
<P>
At present, little more than 40 percent of homes in North
America have personal computers. The companies at the show
expressed hope that with attractive pricing and continued
refinement for ease of use, their technology will catch on with
the non-computer literate.
</P>
<P>
Compaq Computer Corp. president Eckhard Pfeiffer described the
future digital home with a computer center in the basement,
running a network and myriad computers and devices in every room,
from a PC Theater to a device that looks like a cellular phone for
electronic mail. He said Compaq also expects automobiles to be
equipped with a PC and Internet access operated by voice commands.
</P>
<P>
One obstacle to easy use right now is the need to "train" the
software by reading 100 to more than 200 sentences so that the
program learns individual voice patterns.
</P>
<P>
But an IBM marketing manager predicted that within five years
there will be "full duplex communication," where computers perform
requested tasks like finding documents, sending letters and
reading e-mail.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft chairman Bill Gates also said that speech recognition
would be one of the important technical advances of the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
