<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries in the past few
days:
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Exports of Uruguayan beef and mutton were 244,670
tons until November 9, a 27.5 percent increase over the same
period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The exports earned 411 million U.S. dollars, against 332.4
million dollars in 1996, a 24 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
Meat exports are expected to surpass a record of 270,000 tons
by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Foreign and domestic investments in Argentina
dropped 26 percent, from 23 billion dollars in September, to 17
billion dollars in October.
</P>
<P>
The domestic investment, according to the National Stocks
Commission, fell 11.5 percent, from 26.185 billion dollars, to
23.158 billion dollars in the same period.
</P>
<P>
The reduction is attributed to the crisis in mid-October in the
main Asian stock markets.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Exports of the Nicaraguan non-traditional products
will amount to 350 million dollars by the end of this year, a
value similar to that of 1996.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- An economic and commercial exhibition featuring
China will be held November 18-23 in this city.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 home appliances, textiles, ceramics and
machinery will be displayed.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Minera Escondida Co. refined copper output
increased 8.6 percent in October, to 77,945 metric tons, compared
with the same month of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The company's refined copper totaled 778,276 metric tons in the
first 10 months of this year, an 11.1 percent increase over the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Copper products of Escondida made up about 26 percent of the
total national copper output in 1996.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The Bank of Brazil, the main financing agency for
agriculture production, has offered 2.7 billion dollars to finance
the 1997-1998 agricultural season since July, 350 million dollars
more than the previous season.
</P>
<P>
The bank will allocate another 500 million dollars to finance
the expenses of the harvest. The Bank of Brazil has benefited
700,000 farmers throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian government will grant 8.5 billion dollars for the
marketing of agriculture products, a 63 percent increase over the
5.2 billion dollars spent during the previous agricultural
period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
