<HEADLINE> Rome Police Arrest American Paedophile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Rome police said today that an
American citizen accused of sexually abusing two children was
arrested here two days ago following a tip-off by the Federal
Bureau of Investigation (FBI).
</P>
<P>
Joe Daniel Frederich, a 54-year-old computer expert, is wanted
in Texas in the United States where he is accused of raping two
teenagers.
</P>
<P>
The wanted man, who is confined to a wheelchair, drove to Rome
in a caravan, police said.
</P>
<P>
More than 95,000 U.S. dollars in cash, traveler's checks,
several portable computers and disks were discovered in the
caravan.
</P>
<P>
The FBI has been trying to trace Frederich since he left Texas
in April.
</P>
<P>
Frederich was found by Italian police in a hotel on the
outskirts of Rome. The United States Embassy in Rome said he
would be extradited to the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The arrest comes in the wake of a series of tragic paedophilia
cases in Italy which have caused a flurry of concern, and even
calls for schools to be patrolled by vigilantes.
</P>
<P>
Police are still hunting for the remains of a nine-year-old
boy, who was sexually abused and mutilated by a group of
paedophiles in Naples.
</P>
<P>
Further cases of presumed acts of paedophilia came to light
today, one including a Milanese psychologist accused of sexually
abusing five children in his professional care.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi stressed today that a plan
of action was needed involving the public administration, the
government and the media. 
</P>
</TEXT>
