<HEADLINE> Astronauts on Columbia Delay Launch of Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. space shuttle
Columbia's astronauts today delayed releasing a satellite that
observes the sun because of spacecraft problems, the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) said.
</P>
<P>
NASA ordered the crew to wait until Friday before launching the
Spartan satellite from the spacecraft for a two-day-flight.
</P>
<P>
The suspension was ordered after NASA found voltage problems
with Soho, another solar observatory. Soho shut itself down just
hours before Columbia blasted off Wednesday. Ground controllers
had the two-year-old observatory back in operation Thursday
evening.
</P>
<P>
The Spartan will observe the Sun at the same time as Soho does
so scientists can compare measurements. Soho is nearly 1.68
million kilometers from the Earth and 155 million kilometers from
the sun, a point where the gravitational pull of the Earth and the
sun cancel each other.
</P>
<P>
The mission of the satellite is to observe the layer of ionized
gas surrounding the sun called the corona as well as the charged
particles streaming into space from the sun.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, astronauts aboard the Columbia spent their second
day in outer space conducting experiments. Ukrainian astronaut
Leonid Kadenyuk tended flowering mustard plants and pollinated
them.
</P>
<P>
Columbia is carrying 18 mature mustard plants and 162 mustard
seeds. Some of the plants are expected to blossom before the
mission ends. The experiments are intended to shed light on what
kinds of plants might be grown for food on a trip to Mars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
