<HEADLINE> Schuessel's Comments on NATO Membership Spark Repercussions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Foreign Minister
Wolfgan Schuessel's latest comments on the country's proposed NATO
membership have sparked repercussions from political circles of
the country.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published today by the Czech newspaper "Pravo,"
Schuessel commented that Austria's maintenance of neutrality
didn't constitute barriers to the country's joining NATO, but
necessitated changes of the law.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the comments were made public here, the Social
Democratic Party of Austria said Schuessel's remarks were not
serious and didn't conform to the country's constitution as NATO
was still a military bloc. Schuessel doubles as the Vice
Chancellor of Austria.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian constitution stipulates that Austria is not
allowed to join any military blocs.
</P>
<P>
Austrian President Thomas Klestil, a member of the Austrian
People's Party (APP), told a press conference that joining NATO
was not compatible with remaining neutral.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian Freedom Party claimed that Schuessel's comments
were "very irresponsible", and the Green Party described it as
absurd and detrimental to the neutral principle.
</P>
<P>
The issue of NATO membership has long been Austria's focus of
debate.
</P>
<P>
Leading members of the APP have voiced support for Austria's
joining NATO from time to time. But the mainstream of the Social
Democratic Party of Austria, the other party in the ruling
coalition, stands firmly for the country's neutrality.
</P>
<P>
The two ruling parties, widely divided on the application for
NATO membership, have decided to jointly make a report stating
their individual reasons.
</P>
<P>
The report will be submitted next March for discussion by the
country's Federal Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
