<HEADLINE> Ukrainian PM Complains About Trade Conditions With EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian Prime Minister Valery
Pustovoistenko today asked the European Union (EU) to revise its
anti-dumping procedures and the quantitative limits on Ukrainian
goods.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoistenko said while meeting envoys of EU members that the
strict protective tariff policy of the EU had a negative impact on
Ukrainian exports.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoistenko stressed his country did not impose
corresponding anti-dumping measures or quantitative limits on EU's
exports to Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Next to Russia, the EU is Ukraine's second largest trading
partner. The yearly trade volume between the two sides accounts
for 14.3 percent of Ukraine's total. The volume for the first nine
months this year stood at 3.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to Ukraine's Interfax news agency, 70 to 80 percent
of EU's aid to Ukraine was used for public utilities for foreign
exporters, while 20 to 30 percent was used for purchasing
equipment and training expenses of Ukrainian experts.
</P>
<P>
The EU's aid to Ukraine has amounted to 3.16 billion dollars in
recent years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
