<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungarian Government Recognizes Positive Outcome of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The Hungarian government
today gave official recognition to the majority of voters who
recently approved of NATO membership.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the National Assembly on the final result of the
referendum held last Sunday, Kukorelli Istvan, chief of the
national election commission, said among the 49 percent of eight
million eligible voters who took part in the referendum, 85
percent voted for Hungary's entry into the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
The result is valid, said the election chief. The total number
of voters in favor of NATO membership far exceeds the required
legal limit of 25 percent and no fraud or discrepancies were found
in the polling procedure.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the fairness, Russia, Romania, Britain, Belarus and
the Czech Republic sent observers to monitor the first referendum
held in Hungary since 1991.
</P>
<P>
Of the three countries invited to join NATO, Hungary is the
only one to decide by referandum. The other two invitees are
Poland and the Czech Republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
