<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Further Promote Privatization in Food Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- By the end of 1998, 85 percent
of Bulgarian enterprises in the food and flavor industry will be
privatized, Bulgarian Deputy Industry Minister Stefan Stavrev
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Stavrev said private interests control about 67 percent in 148
companies out of a total of 263 enterprises in the sector. A total
of 172 companies are at different stages of privatization.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, 1,174 private partnerships in the
country have been established in the dairy, meat-processing, and
wine industries, sugar refineries, and fishing enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The shares of the first dozen companies in the sector will be
offered on the stock exchange in early 1998, Luchezar Kolev, an
expert in the ministry, said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the ministry show the food and flavor
industries account for 20.8 percent of Bulgaria's
manufacturing. The products of the food and flavor industry make
up 17.4 percent of its exports.
</P>
<P>
The main problem the industry faces is a shortage of raw
materials, said Stavrev. The sugar refineries import 95 percent of
their raw materials. The situation in the canning industry is
similar. The industry is currently operating at only 35-40 percent
of capacity.
</P>
<P>
Other problems in the sector arise from difficulties in
obtaining loans, the poor management of some enterprises and
unfair competition.
</P>
<P>
According to the Deputy Minister, important prerequisites for
the industry's development are equalizing standards with Europe,
the attraction of more investment, and the renovation of
technologies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
