<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberia-ECOMOG Rift Widens on Army Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The rift between Monrovia and
ECOMOG over the restructuring of Liberia's armed forces further
widened as President Charles Taylor today reaffirmed the
government's determination to do the job by itself.
</P>
<P>
The Liberian government will expel anyone in the high command
of the west African peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) that attempted
to challenge or share the constitutional power of the president,
Taylor warned.
</P>
<P>
In a nationwide broadcast from the executive mansion today,
Taylor said he does not expect anyone in ECOMOG to overstep his
authority and remain in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
"There cannot and will not be a parallel authority," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet ministers and legislators listening to the president
applauded, according to a British Broadcasting Corporation
report.
</P>
<P>
Taylor did not mention any names today but his warning came in
the wake of a whirl of words between the government and ECOMOG
Force Commander Major-General Victor Malu over the formation of a
post-war army in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Following a cabinet meeting chaired by Taylor on Wednesday,
the government issued a stern warning to Malu to decease acts
incampatible with the status as a peace-keeping commander.
</P>
<P>
Malu has not yet reacted to the warning, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In his broadcast today, Taylor said Liberia no longer needs a
peace keeping force and only hopes the strengthening of the
capacity of the new government, which was inaugurated on August 2
this year.
</P>
<P>
The president disclosed that the armed forces of Liberia is
currently being restructured by the government.
</P>
<P>
He said the phase on restructuring has already begun and funds
will be made available to the ministry of national defense next
week to renovate barracks around the country.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG was sent to Liberia in the heat of the country's civil
war launched by Taylor at the end of 1989.
</P>
<P>
The force has helped end the seven-year bloody war and put
Taylor to the top seat of the country although the former warlord
reportedly never liked the Nigerian-led ECOMOG for fear of the
expansion of Nigeria's interest in his country and the sub-region
as well.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement that brings peace to Liberia, ECOMOG is
mandated by west African leaders to help restructure and train a
new army for the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
