<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former S. African President Served with Subpoena </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
president P.W. Botha was served today with a subpoena to appear
before the Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC) at a hearing
on the State Security Council in Cape Town on December 5.
</P>
<P>
The five-page subpoena, together with more than 700 pages of
documentation related to the hearing, was handed to a security
official at Botha's retirement home at Wilderness, South African
Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Today's delivery followed Botha's statement earlier this week
that he would not attend the hearing, and his lawyer's refusal to
accept the subpoena delivered in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Two TRC officials flew from Cape Town to George, a city more
than 400 kilometers eastward, and drove to Wilderness to deliver
the subpoena.
</P>
<P>
TRC Deputy Chairman Alex Boraine said in a statement afterward
that it was the TRC's "very deep hope" that Botha would appear at
the hearing.
</P>
<P>
Botha was first subpoenaed to attend the initial round of
State Security Council hearings in Johannesburg earlier this
month, along with fellow members of his former cabinet.
</P>
<P>
His testimony was postponed on the grounds of ill health, and
commission chairman, Desmond Tutu then offered to hold the next
round of hearings in George, only several kilometers away from
Wilderness.
</P>
<P>
However, after Botha indicated his unwillingness to attend,
Tutu said the hearing would continue and if the former state
president failed to appear, he would be prosecuted in terms of
the commission's founding bill.
</P>
<P>
The Promotion of National Unity and Reconciliation Act allows
for a fine or up to two years of imprisonment for disobeying a
subpoena.
</P>
<P>
Botha refused to apologize for the role of its apartheid
government and accused the TRC of being a revenge camp against
the Afrikaner.
</P>
<P>
The TRC is a special court set up to heal the wounds of the
apartheid era. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
