<HEADLINE> Jordan Welcomes Iraq's Decision to Allow UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Jordan today expressed welcome
to Iraq's decision to allow all U.N. inspectors to return to their
monitoring work in Iraq, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Jordanian Minister of State for
Information Affairs Samir Mutawe. The agreement might bring an end
to the standoff between Iraq and the U.N., which lasted about
three weeks, said Mutawe.
</P>
<P>
Jordan really hoped that Iraq's decision could defuse the
tension, Mutawe was quoted as saying to the reporters after a
regular cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
The crisis began after Iraq refused on October 29 to allow the
American inspectors to enter the sites which the U.N. arms
inspectors wanted to inspect. On November 4, Iraq expelled the
American inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The agreement might be the first step for lifting the
sanctions, Mutawe said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and Russia have reached an agreement on Iraq's allowing
the U.N. inspectors to return to Iraq to continue their monitoring
work.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, Russia will work for the lifting of
the seven-year-old U.N. economic sanctions, which bar Iraq from
exporting its oil.
</P>
<P>
The crisis focused world attention on the plight of the Iraqi
people suffering from the sanctions, he said, adding that Jordan,
one of Iraq's largest trade partners, always called for an end to
the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were imposed on Iraq after its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait. Only when the U.N. arms inspectors assert that all
chemical, biological and mass-destruction weapons in Iraq are
destroyed, can the sanctions be lifted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
