<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Militias Accuse Junta of Breaching </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The Kamajors, a group of hunter
militias accused of renewing attacks against soldiers of the
Sierra Leonean military regime, today blamed the junta for
violating cease fire in the country.
</P>
<P>
A Kamajor official, Eddie Mando, said that the traditional
hunters accepted the peace agreement because it was in the best
interest of Sierra Leone and the Kamajors, a report reaching
here said today.
</P>
<P>
The peace accord, which was signed last month in Conakry,
Guinea, calls for a cease fire, disarmament and demobilization of
combatants, as well as reinstatement of ousted President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah in April next year.
</P>
<P>
According to Mando, soldiers of the junta, which seized power
in the May 25 coup, are attacking the Kamajors and innocent
civilians as part of their "tricks".
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that cease-fire violations in clashes
between the two sides were straining the fragile peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The allegation runs counter to reports of renewed attacks by
the Kamajors against junta forces over the past days at the
diamond mining town of Tongo in southeast of the country.
</P>
<P>
The British Broadcasting Corporation Wednesday quoted
residents who fled Tongo as saying that the Kamajors had captured
all the roads leading to the town.
</P>
<P>
The Kamajors have also warned all the civilians to leave the
town by November 28 before they launch an all-out attack on the
junta forces who have held the town since the coup.
</P>
<P>
A junta spokesman reportedly said earlier that the ruling
Armed Forces Revolutionary Council will report the incidents to
the west African peace-keeping force (ECOMOG).
</P>
<P>
There has been no response heard from ECOMOG which is mandated
by the west African countries to monitor the peace process in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a visit to Freetown today by west African foreign
ministers who brokered the Conakry agreement has been postponed.
</P>
<P>
The visit of the foreign ministers of Nigeria, Ghana, Cote
d'Ivoire, Guinea and Liberia is designed to strengthen the
agreement while the junta differs with ECOMOG over whether the
national army of Sierra Leone should be disarmed.
</P>
<P>
The junta has said the visit may take place on November 28.
</P>
</TEXT>
