<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Stresses Importance of Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu noted today that the latest terror attack
in Jerusalem reminded the Jewish state again of the need to fight
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference held in Prime Minister's Office
this afternoon, Netanyahu said that Israel can not accept terror
activities such as last night shooting, in which one Jewish
religious student was killed and another was seriously wounded in
the Muslim quarter of East Jerusalem's Old City.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that the security patrol in the country will
be strengthened. And he urged the Palestinian National Authority
to continue fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
So far no one claimed responsibility for the attack, but it
was suspected to be carried out by Muslim militants.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu held talks today with top cabinet ministers and
security officials on the attack. During the meeting, Jerusalem
mayor Ehud Olmert demanded that Israel suspend recent resumed
peace talks with Palestinians, saying they are not keeping their
obligation to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Netanyahu also addressed the issue of
the crisis in the ruling Likud Party. He suggested that a
referendum of Likud members around the country should be held to
decide what is the best way to elect Likud candidates for the
Knesset (parliament).
</P>
<P>
He said that the result of the referendum will be offered to
the party central committee. And the committee will made its
decision if it is necessary to restore the election primaries,
which was dumped last Wednesday at a controversial party
convention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
