<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Sacks Officials for Irregularities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone' military junta
has sacked one and suspended eight top military officials, mostly
in connection with financial irregularities.
</P>
<P>
Alfred Muna, secretary-general of the Boat Owner's Association
and member of the military's Supreme Council of State, was sacked
for his involvement in "some dubious activities," one state house
aide said, quoted by a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The military leader, Major Johnny Paul Koroma, on Sunday
suspended eight other council members and placed them under "mass
arrest", the report said.
</P>
<P>
The eight "honorables" are alleged to have "undermined the
revenue-generating capacity" of the diamond-rich country's
Ministry of Mines and Mineral Resources.
</P>
<P>
No official explanation has been given for the suspensions,
but military sources are quoted as saying the eight had "set in
place a reign of anarchy inconsistent with state stability".
</P>
<P>
For the past three months, mining ministry officials have
refused to travel to diamond mining areas in the east, claiming
they fear that senior military members are seen in the area with
heavily armed bodyguards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
