<HEADLINE> Zambian Prisons in Deplorable State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Most Zambia's prisons are in
such deplorable state that they have become a breeding place for
hard core criminals instead of reformation, some parliament
members told parliament here today.
</P>
<P>
Sikota Wina from the ruling party said that prisons have
become places of anguish, torture and misery that efforts to
reform prisoners will be futile.
</P>
<P>
Moving a motion for the house to adopt the report of the
Committee on Social Services, Wina said there is hopelessness and
widespread starvation in prisons so that prisoners are sometimes
forced to eat wild creatures such as lizards, snakes and owls.
</P>
<P>
He recommended that the entire prison service should be
overhauled so that government's well intended purpose of
reforming prisoners could be achieved.
</P>
<P>
Independent parliament member Charity Mwansa cited Kabwe
Maximum Security Prison which was intended to accommodate 450 but
there are now 970 prisoners while Kabwe Central Prison has 540
instead of 280 prisoners.
</P>
<P>
She said Lusaka Central accommodates 1,271 instead of the
intended 260 prisoners.
</P>
<P>
She wondered how prisoners can be treated so badly and called
on the government to create better living standards for
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Another parliament member urged the government to engage
prisoners in production so that they can be self-reliant.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the prisons are too congested and too
filthy for human habitation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
