<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopians Suffer From Fluoride-related Ailments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 20 (Xinhua) -- About 90 percent of the
people residing in the Ethiopian Rift Valley areas suffer from
the effect of fluoride which attacks bone and tooth, Ethiopian
Minister of Water Resources Shiferan Jarso said today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, when opening an
international workshop on fluoride in Nazreth, 90 kms away from
Addis Ababa, the minister said people living in the Rift Valley
areas are the most vulnerable to diseases caused by fluoride as
they use underground water.
</P>
<P>
He said if the amount of fluoride contained in a liter of
water exceeds 1.5 milligram, it will be dangerous to health,
adding that there are water wells in the area with fluoride
content of over 20 grams per liter.
</P>
<P>
The minister said fluoride causes tooth-decay in children
below the age of 12 and could expose to bone diseases in the case
of adults above the age of 45.
</P>
<P>
He told the participants that efforts to harness the river
Awash to supply fluoride-free water to residents in towns will
further be enhanced alongside endeavors to create favorable
conditions whereby the scientific techniques used elsewhere will
be adopted to filter the water the rural populace uses.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is attended by participants from South Africa,
India, Thailand, Sri Lanka, Tanzania, Uganda and Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The first international workshop on fluoride was held in
Arusha, Tanzania two years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Results of Men's World Cup Giant Slalom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
