<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austrian Wins World Cup Giant Slalom in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Hermann Maier won
the men's World Cup Alpine skiing giant slalom Thursday at Park
City, Utah, finishing the run in a total of 2:43.99.
</P>
<P>
Maier, who posted the fastest first-leg time of 1:22.24,
charged down the course in 1:21.75 in the final run to beat the
field by nearly two seconds.
</P>
<P>
The victory took the Austrian, who finished third in the giant
slalom at Tignes, France, to the first place in the World Cup
giant slalom standings and first place in the overall standings.
</P>
<P>
Norway's Kjetil Andre Aamodt, who sliced through the course in
1:21.13 to jump from 28th after the first run to second place with
a combined time of 2:45.79.
</P>
<P>
Third place went to Canadian Thomas Grandi, who finished the
second run in 1:23.37 for a combined time of 2:46.31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
