<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Winter Olympic Downhill Issue to Be Decided on December 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The dispute over the length of
the men's downhill course will be resloved by December 1, the
Nagano Olympic organizing committee executives said here on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Hironoshin Furuhashi, head of a five-man group formed to decide
the issue, said that the body will tour the upper half of the
2,696-meter Mount Karamatsu next Monday and decide upon the height
of the downhill course's starting gate.
</P>
<P>
NAOC offered earlier this month to move the start gate from
1,680 meters above sea level to 1,740 meters, provided that the
course does not encroach upon a protected national park area.
</P>
<P>
The International Ski Federation (FIS) responded by proposing
four alternative start points at 1,760, 1,764, 1782 or 1,794
meters. But with these options, passing through the protected
area is unavoidable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
