<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Isiah Thomas Resigns from Raptors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Isiah Thomas, former
superstar of National Basketball Association (NBA) champions
Detroit Pistons, resigned Thursday as general manager of the
Toronto Raptors.
</P>
<P>
Thomas, one of the NBA All-time best 50, was set to sell his
minor nine percent interest in the team to majority owner Allan
Slaight, a Raptors spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Thomas, whose post in the struggling Raptors was executive vice
president, had a dispute with Slaight over ownership and
management issues. His bid for buying majority control of the
team from Slaight, who owns 81 percent of the franchise, was also
declined.
</P>
<P>
Their relationship was reportedly strained ever since.
</P>
<P>
"It is with regret that we say good-bye to Isiah Thomas,"
Slaight said in a statement. "He has made an important
contribution to this franchise and we will miss him."
</P>
<P>
Thomas, came to Raptors as a manager on May 24, 1994, is a
housename in Toronto for his constructive work in the team.
Raptors' all-time leading scorer Damon Stoudamire, selected by
Thomas as the seventh pick overall in first round in 1995, said
Thomas was the only reason he stayed in Raptors.
</P>
<P>
The NBC reportedly offers Thomas an analyst job on NBA
telecasts and a show on MSNBC, one of the network's cable
outlets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
