<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: U.S. to "Wait and See" Iraq's Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
WASHINGTON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton,
 wary of Iraq's permission to allow U.N. weapons inspectors
 including Americans back on their work, said on Thursday that he
 will "wait and see" Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's next
 action.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's Revolutionary Command Council earlier issued a
 statement, saying "Iraq has accepted the return of U.N. Special
 Commission (UNSCOM) inspectors, including the Americans," to
 Baghdad and resume their work.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said it was not enough to just make a statement by
 Saddam Hussein, "We will wait and see" if he does what he says, he
 emphasized.
</P>
<P>
"The United States must remain and will remain resolute in
 our determination to prevent him from threatening his neighbors
 of the world with nuclear, chemical or biological weapons," the
 president said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the White House welcomed Iraq's decision to reverse
 his ban on American weapons inspectors, saying it was "an
 encouraging development."
</P>
<P>
But the statement "must ultimately be tested by what Saddam
 Hussein does," White House spokeswoman Anne Luzzatto said. "We
 have to see how it unfolds."
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, now in Geneva
 attending an emergency meeting with four other permanent members
 of U.N. Security Council on the weapons inspection crisis,
 called Iraq's decision "a step in the right direction."
</P>
<P>
"It's the secretary's view that the announcement out of
 Baghdad is a step in the right direction," said State Department
 spokesman James Rubin, who is accompanying Albright on her world
 travel.
</P>
<P>
"Our objective was to see the unconditional return of the
 U.N. inspectors. Our strategy was to combine intensive
 diplomacy, that is the unity of the major powers, with a robust
 military posture and if the inspectors return, then our
 objectives will have been met," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Open Stock Mart in Early 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 19 (Xinhua) -- the long-awaited stock
market will open early next year, after the country's Capital
Markets and Securities Authority (CMSA) approved the first
listing, Daily News said today.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania Oxygen Ltd (TOL), a state-owned company regarded as a
blue chip stock by local standards, had been pressing for urgent
approval of its prospectus in order to fund expansion through an
initial public offering of shares.
</P>
<P>
"The prospectus has been approved. We're waiting for the final
version. We'll do a timetable to indicate when shares will be
traded," said Hamisi Kibola, director of legal services for CMSA
and chief executive officer of the Dar es Salaam Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
"In terms of sequence, we're talking of TOL as the first
company (for listing)," Kibola was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kibola said that the listing process could take around three
weeks, but the exchange is unlikely to be opened next month
because this is too close to the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
The most likely date is now early 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
TOL's legal services manager, Lau Masha, said the company's
prospectus includes an ambitious expansion program involving
mineral water, industrial gases and carbon dioxide.
</P>
<P>
"For TOL, going onto the exchange, we're looking to raise
capital for the expansion project," Masha said. He declined to
give details of how much money TOL is hoping to raise.
</P>
<P>
TOL's sales turnover in 1996 was 2.7 billion shillings (about
4.3 million US dollars), up from 2.4 billion in 1995, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kibola said that after TOL, the next company likely to trade
on the exchange would likely be Tanzania Breweries Ltd.
</P>
<P>
The third and fourth companies expected to be listed are
Tanzania Cigarette Company and Agip Tanzania Ltd, he said.
</P>
