<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' GNP Up by 2.5-3 Percent This Year: IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 21 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) predicts an economic growth of only 2.5 to 3.0 percent in
the Philippines this year, far below the government's adjusted
target of 5.5 to 6.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Manila Times today quoted a 12-page report of an IMF team
which reviewed the country's recent economic performance last week
as saying that the IMF was scaling down its projection for the
country's gross national product (GNP) due to the currency crisis
and surging interest rates.
</P>
<P>
For next year, the IMF team sees the growth rate at 4.0 to 4.5
percent, again below the government's projected target of 6.5
percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF team pointed out, however, that its growth estimates
for the Philippines are still higher than projections for other
Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
For instance, the IMF expects Thailand to grow by only 1.5
percent this year and Indonesia by 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
GNP, a measure of economic output, is the sum of goods and
services produced by a country's nationals, including
contributions from citizens working overseas.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines last year posted a GNP growth rate of 6.8
percent, the strongest economic performance since 1988.
</P>
<P>
Government planners originally hoped the economy will grow by
seven to eight percent this year. They had to scale down the
target to only 5.5 to 6.0 percent after a region-wide currency
meltdown resulted in massive outflow of funds and surging interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
There were signs of a slowdown even before the crisis gripped
the region in July. The GNP in the first half of the year grew by
only 5.9 percent compared to 7.5 percent in the same period last
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
