<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Berger: U.S. not Bound by Russian-Iraqi Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. National Security
Advisor Samuel Berger said on Thursday that Washington would not
be bound by any agreement between Russia and Iraq that led to
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's decision to permit U.N. weapons
inspectors back to his country and resume their work.
</P>
<P>
"That is an understanding between Russia and Iraq. It is not
binding on us or the U.N.. It is not something we are obligated to
in any respect," Berger told reporters at a White House news
briefing.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized President Bill Clinton's earlier statement that
the United States would "wait and see" if Saddam Hussein acts on
what he says. "We must be quite cautious about this. This is not
over," Berger said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said at the White House this morning that it was not
enough to just make a statement by Saddam Hussein, "We will wait
and see" if he does what he says, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The United States must remain and will remain resolute in
our determination to prevent him from threatening his neighbors
of the world with nuclear, chemical or biological weapons," the
president said.
</P>
<P>
White House officials, while calling Iraq's decision to allow
U.N. weapons inspectors including Americans back to resume their
work "an encouraging development," also said they "have to see
how it unfolds."
</P>
<P>
The statement made by Iraq's Revolutionary Command Council on
the resumption of U.N. weapons inspections "must ultimately be
tested by what Saddam Hussein does," White House spokeswoman Anne
Luzzatto said.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, now in Geneva
attending an emergency meeting with four other permanent members
of U.N. Security Council on the weapons inspection crisis,
called Iraq's decision "a step in the right direction."
</P>
<P>
"It's the secretary's view that the announcement out of
Baghdad is a step in the right direction," said State Department
spokesman James Rubin, who is accompanying Albright on her world
travel.
</P>
<P>
"Our objective was to see the unconditional return of the
U.N. inspectors. Our strategy was to combine intensive
diplomacy, that is the unity of the major powers, with a robust
military posture and if the inspectors return, then our
objectives will have been met," he said.
</P>
<P>
Albright later said at a short news conference in Geneva that
Saddam Hussein seemed to have "reversed course" in his standoff
with the United Nations over the weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
"It appears that Saddam Hussein has reversed course and that
the U.N. inspectors will be able to go in and do their work
unconditionally," she said.
</P>
<P>
Berger, as if to underscore that the United States is not yet
ready to ease its vigilance over the weapons inspection crisis,
told reporters that U.S. air power in the Gulf would be further
reinforced and U-2 spy planes will continue their mission for
the United Nations to monitor Iraq's weapons programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
