<HEADLINE> Afro-American Museum Considers Displaying Burned Cross </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The Federal Bureau of
Investigation has joined the state investigation into who put a
charred cross on the grounds of the National Afro-American Museum
and Cultural Center in Wilberforce, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
Museum officials are considering putting the 5-foot wooden
cross on display at the museum. Discovered Tuesday morning, the
cross was scrawled with racial slurs, "KKK" and a swastika. It was
slightly charred on the back and there was a smell of kerosene in
the air.
</P>
<P>
"(People) think those kinds of things happened in the Stone Age
and they could never happen again," The Associated Press quoted
museum spokesman Michael Sampson saying.
</P>
<P>
An FBI agent joined the state Highway Patrol's investigation
because of a possible civil rights violation.
</P>
<P>
The museum, which opened in 1988, was chartered by Congress
with a goal of educating visitors about black history and culture.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, a man was arrested and accused of plotting to bomb the
museum on Martin Luther King Day.
</P>
<P>
The museum is located on the old campus of Wilberforce
University, 20 miles east of Dayton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
