<HEADLINE> US to Send Air Expeditionary Force to Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
sending more warplanes to the Gulf this weekend as still another
reinforcement even after Iraq has agreed to allow U.N. weapons
inspectors including Americans back to resume their work, Pentagon
officials said today.
</P>
<P>
Twelve F-15 fighters, 18 F-16 fighters and two B-1 bombers, to
form an air expeditionary force, will be dispatched to Bahrain,
where an air base will be used for their operation.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied with the air expeditionary force will be four
KC-135 aerial refueling planes.
</P>
<P>
Six F-117a stealth fighters and six B-52 bombers have left
their Air Force bases in the United States and will arrive at
their separate destinations in Kuwait and the Indian Ocean island
of Diego Garcia today.
</P>
<P>
The continuing build-up will bring U.S. air and naval forces in
the Gulf to more than 300 warplanes and 22 warships.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton earlier in the week ordered the F-117a
stealth fighters and B-52 bombers to the Gulf and authorized
Commander Anthony Zinni to form an additional air expeditionary
force to the Gulf if necessary.
</P>
<P>
And Zinni decided it was necessary to send the additional
aircraft as an air expeditionary force to the region. Defense
Secretary William Cohen signed the order for deployment of the
expeditionary force.
</P>
<P>
The United States also decided to send additional Patriot
anti-aircraft missile launchers to Bahrain to protect the air
expeditionary force with 32 warplanes.
</P>
<P>
Army Col. Richard Bridges, a Pentagon spokesman, said the
additional firing unit would be added to a Patriot battery already
stationed in Bahrain. The missiles could be used to intercept any
Scud missiles fired by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Washington is wary of Iraq's decision to let American weapons
inspectors back to Baghdad to resume their work and adopted a
"wait and see" attitude toward Iraq's next step if it acts on its
words.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said it was not enough to just make a statement on the
resumption of the weapons inspections. "We will wait and see," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The United States must remain and will remain resolute in our
determination to prevent him from threatening his neighbors of the
world with nuclear, chemical or biological weapons," the president
said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's Security Advisor Samuel Berger said the United States
would not be bound by any agreements between the Iraqis and
Russians who had persuaded the Iraqis to agree in allowing weapons
inspectors back for their work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
