<HEADLINE> Iraq: Arms Inspectors Can Return to Iraq Immediately </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Ambassador to the
United Nations Nizar Hamdoon today informed the Security Council
that all the arms inspectors can return to Iraq and resume their
work immediately.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Hamdoon said, " We think that the
crisis is over. Today I delivered to the President of the
Security Council the decision of the Government of Iraq to
invite the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) back in
its usual work, its usual teams and start working, effective today."
</P>
<P>
"We have invited the UNSCOM and its entire membership,
including Americans," he added.
</P>
<P>
The standoff between the United Nations and Iraq began on
October 29 when Iraq ordered to expel six American members of
UNSCOM in the country, which led to the pulling out of its
weapons teams.
</P>
<P>
Hamdoon said, "We hope that there will be a better climate
now for more cooperative relations between Iraq and the UNSCOM
people."
</P>
<P>
Asked about what has caused Iraq to make such a decision,
Hamdoon said, "The Russians committed themselves to work hard on
the weapons files that have to do with the UNSCOM work and
therefore for the lifting of the sanctions."
</P>
<P>
He denied that the threat of American military buildup in the
Gulf area affected Iraqi decision-making. 
</P>
</TEXT>
