<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Jobs Summit Gives EU Another Tough Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU),
which has been devoted to the integration of European countries to
create a stronger Europe, has been given another chance by the
ongoing EU jobs summit to see how tough a job it is doing.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state and government of EU member countries, who
arrived here today to discuss joint actions to deal with the
challenging issue of unemployment in Europe, should and must
realize that they are also representatives of different EU member
countries.
</P>
<P>
Germany seemed to be the first one to break the harmonious tune
orchestrated by the EU's executive body, the European Commission,
which has proposed "verifiable and quantifiable" EU-wide targets
for curbing the serious unemployment problem.
</P>
<P>
It has given the impression that it believes the jobs summit is
virtually a luxury by saying that employment policy must remain
the responsibility of national governments.
</P>
<P>
But France is trying to explain its different logic behind its
insistence that the issue of unemployment be put high on the EU's
agenda.
</P>
<P>
Paris argues that the ordinary people want to improve their
lives in the first place, after which they might be able to give a
thought to the Bonn-advocated monetary discipline in the future
European single currency.
</P>
<P>
The problem also lies in the fact that Germany and France are
not holding firmly alone in their respective stands. Instead they
are being followed each by differing groups of EU countries, which
also have their national interests in mind, if there is one thing
for certain about the EU.
</P>
<P>
With some 18 million people in the EU listed as unemployed, the
heads of state and government haven't got too much time to differ
on the issue of employment and other ones, with less than six
months to go before the EU decides on which nations will be chosen
to launch the euro.
</P>
<P>
They came to the two-day extraordinary Council of Europe
meeting to seek agreement on dealing with the issue though there
seemed to be little agreement they could reach. And there seems
little chance that most of EU citizens, who would rather stay home
jobless, will be encouraged to leave their countries for work.
</P>
<P>
Thus has posed the most challenging issue to Jacques Santer,
president of the European Commission, who always calls for joint
actions by different EU countries to solve the problem of
unemployment, which has hardly increased during the past two
decades.
</P>
<P>
It is quite possible that Santer wants to tackle the issue
within the framework of a United States of Europe, though
different EU countries are just intent on solving their different
problems in their own ways with the support or aid given by
European institutions.
</P>
<P>
Spain, with Europe's highest jobless rate but also the most
fruitful achievement in creating jobs, attended the jobs summit
with a particular interest of its own.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish government, which has declared 1997 as the "year of
employment," succeeded in getting both employers and unions to
agree to a labor law which restricts the country's generous system
of "payoffs for layoffs."
</P>
<P>
Padraig Flynn, EU commissioner for social affairs and
employment, told reporters today that they had to take action to
deal with the problem and that he was "optimistic" about the
prospects of employment in Europe. But he was in too much a hurry
to explain why. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
