<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Tries Tagging on Early Released Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The British government
announced plans today to let some short-sentenced criminals out of
jail early provided they agree to wear electronic tags.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Jack Straw said some 6,000 short-term
prisoners would be electronically tagged after being released from
jail two months early.
</P>
<P>
The move was aimed at curbing a rocketing prison population, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The number of prisoners in British jails has risen from 3,400
to 63,000 since the new Labor government took power in May, a
figure twice as much as the government had anticipated.
</P>
<P>
The early released prisoners would be tagged for the rest of
their sentence, and required to spend at least nine hours a day at
home, Straw said in a statement to the parliament.
</P>
<P>
"The case for introducing an element of tagging into the last
part of a short-term prison sentence is...very strong in any
event," he added.
</P>
<P>
The previous Conservative government had already introduced
trials in three areas of the country to allow courts to impose a
new penalty of a curfew order enforced by electronic monitoring as
an alternative to jail or a fine. Straw announced he was extending
this trial to four new areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
