<HEADLINE> Clinton Seeks Religious Leaders' Help in Race Harmony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today asked religious leaders to help overcome racial problems.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, at a White House breakfast with about 130 religious
leaders and theologians of various faiths, urged Americans today
to prepare for the day that the nation has no single race as a
majority.
</P>
<P>
The president said the nation faces a dire future if it turns a
blind eye to its growing, diverse population and fails to deal
with racial divisions.
</P>
<P>
Clinton called on churches to draw Americans into a year-long
national drive for racial harmony that he launched in June.
</P>
<P>
"America has become markedly more diverse racially, and that
means we're becoming markedly more diverse culturally, and in
religious terms as well," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that one state, Hawaii, already has no racial
group as a majority, and within a few years, California, the
country's biggest state with 13 percent of its population, will
follow. The nation will not have a white majority within probably
50 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We'd best be ready," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said there are still "racial disparities" in the United
States in the credit practices of banks, in the access to higher
education, and in the earnings in workplace.
</P>
<P>
He said, "It is clear that our attempt to keep making progress
toward the American dream requires us to make progress on the
issues of race and all those that are related."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "We started with a Constitution that we couldn't
live up to."
</P>
<P>
"And our whole life as a nation has been an effort punctuated
by crisis after crisis after crisis to move our collective life
closer to where we said we believed in over 200 years ago," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
