<HEADLINE> Cohen: No More Military Reinforcement in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen said on Thursday that he saw no need to dispatch
more military reinforcement to the Persian Gulf region after a
32-warplane air expeditionary force was announced to go to the
region.
</P>
<P>
"After today I would not see the need for additional aircraft
or assets unless the commander-in-chief of Central Command
should require it," Cohen said after paying a courtesy call to
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon officials said earlier that the air expeditionary
force, formed with 12 F-15 fighters, 18 F-16 fighters and two
B-1 bombers, would be sending to Bahrain this weekend.
</P>
<P>
There would also be four KC-135 aerial refueling planes to
accompany the expeditionary force, they said.
</P>
<P>
For protection of the "air expeditionary unit", the Pentagon
also decided to send additional Patriot anti-aircraft missile
launchers to Bahrain, the Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
Six F-117a stealth fighters and six B-52 bombers have left
their Air Force bases in the United States and will arrive in
their separate destinations in Kuwait and the Indian Ocean island
of Diego Garcia on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The continuing military build-up would push U.S. air and
naval forces in the Gulf to more than 300 warplanes and 22
warships.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton earlier in the week ordered the F-117a
stealth fighters and B-52 bombers to the Gulf and authorized
Commander Anthony Zinni to form an additional air expeditionary
force to the Gulf if necessary.
</P>
<P>
And Zinni decided it was necessary to send the additional
aircraft as an air expeditionary force to the region. Defense
Secretary William Cohen signed the order for deployment of the
expeditionary force.
</P>
<P>
The latest military move took place even after Iraq announced
early on Thursday that it agreed to allow U.N. weapons
inspectors including Americans to return to Baghdad and resume
their work.
</P>
<P>
Washington is wary of Iraq's decision to let American
weapons inspectors back to Baghdad to resume their work and
adopted a "wait and see" attitude toward Iraq's next step if it
acts on its words.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said it was not enough to just make a statement on
the resumption of the weapons inspections. "We will wait and
see."
</P>
<P>
"The United States must remain and will remain resolute in
our determination to prevent him from threatening his neighbors
of the world with nuclear, chemical or biological weapons," the
president said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's Security Advisor Samuel Berger said the United
States would not be bound by any agreements between the Iraqis
and Russian who had persuaded the Iraqis to agree to allow
weapons inspectors back for their work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
