<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Tumbles to Four-Month Lows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 20 (Xinhua) -- The settlement of the
Iraq-U.S. military confrontation pushed crude oil futures tumbled
today to four-month lows on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Iraq agreed to allow American weapon
inspectors back into the country, apparently averting a military
conflict that could have halted the flow of oil.
</P>
<P>
Gasoline, heating oil and natural gas futures also fell sharply.
</P>
<P>
December crude settled 64 cents lower at 19.16 U.S. dollars a
barrel, after falling as low as 19.05 U.S. dollars, the lowest
since July 22; December unleaded gasoline fell 1.43 cents to 57.22
cents a gallon; December heating oil fell 1.22 cents to 55.45
cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
Traders were speculating that the U.N. oil-for-food plan for
Iraq would allow Iraq to export 3 billion U.S. dollars in oil over
six months, up from 2 billion U.S. dollars previously.
</P>
<P>
The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) also
is meeting next week in Indonesia, and Saudi Arabia, one of the
world's largest exporters, already has signaled it will seek to
significantly boost daily export quotas, according to market
sources.
</P>
<P>
Natural gas futures also fell sharply as long-range forecasts
for above-normal temperatures in major U.S. heating regions raised
expectations inventories in storage will be able to meet winter
demand. December natural gas fell 15.3 cents to 2.708 U.S. dollars
for each 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
