<HEADLINE> U.S. Indicates Pause of Sending More Forces to Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen said here today that he anticipates no need to send
more "military assets" to the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
"After today I would not see the need for additional aircraft
or assets unless the commander-in-chief of Central Command should
require it," he told reporters after a brief meeting with U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said there have been additional aircraft sent to the region
in recent days, which would represent "a sufficient complement"
of the United States in the region for the time being.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. forces will stay as long as there is full
compliance with the U.N. resolutions on the part of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has increased its military presence in the region to
keep pressure on Iraq for its cooperation with the U.N. in
inspecting its weapons.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said one reason for U.S. forces to stay there is the
movement of Iraq's surface missiles which could threaten U.S. U-2
aircraft flown over Iraq on a U.N. banner.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the possibility of allowing Iraq to sell more oil
for additional humanitarian relief, Cohen said ways to help
alleviate Iraqi people's sufferings can only be explored when
there is full compliance with relevant U.N. resolutions by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said it is not because Iraqi President Saddam Hussein is
in power that the U.S. does not agree to lift sanctions on Iraq ,
but it is because Iraq possesses chemical and biological weapons
discovered by U.N. inspectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
