<HEADLINE> Clinton Endorses Patient Rights Recommendation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- In a most sweeping health
care reform effort since 1994, U.S. President Bill Clinton today
voiced support to a wide-ranging patient "bill of rights" proposed
by a 34-member presidential commission.
</P>
<P>
Clinton urged Congress to enact the reform proposals and called
on private industry to observe them.
</P>
<P>
The reforms require health plans to pay for emergency room
visits, to provide full information on their doctors and financial
incentives, and to accept outside appeal procedures for various
grievances.
</P>
<P>
The measures also give patients the right to consult enough
doctors to avoid unreasonable waits, to stay with the same doctor
when forced to switch health plans, and to keep their medical
records private.
</P>
<P>
Administration officials said the proposals -- a "bill of
rights" for patients -- will be implemented through the
accreditation process, voluntary compliance or, where necessary,
by legislation
</P>
<P>
Clinton acknowledged the reforms are part of an effort to
enact partial health care reform following his 1994 defeat on a
comprehensive plan.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "While people may not have wanted to bite the
whole apple at once in 1994, almost the whole populace wants to
keep nibbling away at the apple until we actually have solved the
problems of cost, accessibility and quality for all responsible
American citizens."
</P>
<P>
The recommended plan is expected to meet potential opposition
from business and congressional conservatives in enacting key
elements which they say will increase health care costs for
employers, although Clinton said many corporate leaders support
the commission's report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
