<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Officials Continues Meeting on Free Trade, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VANCOUVER, Canada, November 20 (Xinhua) -- Senior officials
from 18 economies of the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC)
forum today met for a second day, focusing on economic technical
cooperation and selection of sectors for early liberalization.
</P>
<P>
The officials are making their last ditch of efforts in
preparing a final document for a ministerial meeting scheduled on
Friday and Saturday, which is followed by an informal meeting of
APEC leaders next week.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will decide how to strengthen the economic
technical cooperation among the members and attempt to identify
priority sectors among the 41 proposals which the senior officials
came up with at their last meeting in Singapore in October.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the officials spent a whole day discussing the
agendas and a number of preparatory documents for the ministerial
meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Consequently in this meeting, we don't intend to take on any
of the decision-making or complex policy discussions that the
ministers will have during the weekend," a senior Canadian
official told reporters Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The officials focused on three "substantive issues", including
the early voluntary sectoral liberalization, the infrastructure
cooperation and the sustainable development, he said.
</P>
<P>
The participants have agreed to narrow the selection of the
sectors from 41 to less than 20 proposals and they will continue
discussion on this subject.
</P>
<P>
However, other sources said that the officials are now focusing
on 15 proposals. Each proposal does not necessarily mean
liberalization in one product sector.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, APEC leaders agreed in Subic Bay of the Philipines
that ministers will identify sectors where early voluntary
liberalization would have a positive impact on trade, investment
and economic growth and submit recommendations to the leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian official noted that Canada pursued a number of
priorities in early liberalization sectors ranging from primary
and manufactured goods.
</P>
<P>
"We have been in forefront efforts to identify fishery sector,
wood product, oil seeds and primary product material," he said.
</P>
<P>
APEC members have not reached consensus on a single sector so
far because many are expected to protect their interests in
sensitive sectors.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that fairly broad support have been shown for
early voluntary liberalization in toys, chemicals, and
environmental goods and services.
</P>
<P>
They said that sectors included in the 15 proposals will be
divided into three stages for early liberalization.
</P>
<P>
On the economic technical cooperation, the officials examined
the issue of possible mechanism, and "will probably be proposing a
sub-committee of the senior officials," the Canadian official
said.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis in South East Asia was another major
subject for the discussions.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, deputy finance ministers from Asia and the U.S.,
along with top officials from the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) agreed to a framework for regional cooperation to promote
financial stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, the Canadian official said, was "greeted with a
good deal of pleasure by officials here" and send a strong,
confidence-building message about liveralizing trade, but it still
needs to be studied.
</P>
<P>
The APEC, which was initiated in 1989, now groups Australia,
Brunei Darussalam, Canada, Chile, China, China's Hong Kong,
Indonesia, Republic of Korea, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Papua
New Guinea, Philipines, Singapore, Chinese Taipei, Thailand and
the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971121.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Call on Passing 1998 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 20 (Xinhua) -- President Boris Yeltsin on
Thursday afternoon called on the State Duma to pass the 1998 draft
budget, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In a televised interview Yeltsin said "I request the State Duma
deputies and Speaker Gennady Seleznyov to pass the budget and
close this item of the agenda."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin hopes that the newly-appointed Finance Minister Mikhail
Zadornov, also Duma Budgetary Committee Chairman, will attend "to
the financial weak points in the government's operation."
</P>
<P>
The State Duma threatened that the passage of the 1998 budget
would be linked with the controversial 450,000 US dollars book
deal, which were involved five top governmental officials,
including Anatoly Chubais, the First Deputy Prime Minister and
Finance Minister.
</P>
<P>
The Russian president said he had decided that First Deputy
Prime Ministers Anatoly Chubais and Boris Nemtsov would not also
head ministries.
</P>
<P>
Another report said, Yeltsin on Thursday appointed Viktoriya
Mitina deputy head of the presidential administration.
</P>
<P>
Mitina's predecessor was Alexander Kazakov, who was one of the
writers of the book on Russian privatization and dismissed by the
president on November 14.
</P>
<P>
Mitina was graduated from the Moscow Institute of Electronic
Technology in 1972, and was first deputy chairperson of the
Zelenograd Soviet in 1990-1991.
</P>
<P>
Mitina has been deputy prefect of Zelenograd Administrative
Area in Moscow in charge of science, industry, entrepreneurship,
land relations, media and political and interest groups.
</P>
<P>
She campaigned for Boris Yeltsin in all elections since 1989,
from the USSR Supreme Soviet to presidential elections in 1991 and
1996.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Yeltsin also signed a decree appointing
Sergei Kiriyenko Fuel and Energy Minister. He was the First Deputy
of the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today the president removed Anatoly Chubais from the
post of Finance Minister and appointed Mikhail Zadornov to the
post. Chubais, who was involved in a scandal relating a high
payment for a book on Russian privatization, remains the first
deputy prime minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
