<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-20 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: U.S. to "Wait and See" Iraq's Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
WASHINGTON, November 20 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton,
 wary of Iraq's permission to allow U.N. weapons inspectors
 including Americans back on their work, said on Thursday that he
 will "wait and see" Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's next
 action.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's Revolutionary Command Council earlier issued a
 statement, saying "Iraq has accepted the return of U.N. Special
 Commission (UNSCOM) inspectors, including the Americans," to
 Baghdad and resume their work.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said it was not enough to just make a statement by
 Saddam Hussein, "We will wait and see" if he does what he says, he
 emphasized.
</P>
<P>
"The United States must remain and will remain resolute in
 our determination to prevent him from threatening his neighbors
 of the world with nuclear, chemical or biological weapons," the
 president said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the White House welcomed Iraq's decision to reverse
 his ban on American weapons inspectors, saying it was "an
 encouraging development."
</P>
<P>
But the statement "must ultimately be tested by what Saddam
 Hussein does," White House spokeswoman Anne Luzzatto said. "We
 have to see how it unfolds."
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, now in Geneva
 attending an emergency meeting with four other permanent members
 of U.N. Security Council on the weapons inspection crisis,
 called Iraq's decision "a step in the right direction."
</P>
<P>
"It's the secretary's view that the announcement out of
 Baghdad is a step in the right direction," said State Department
 spokesman James Rubin, who is accompanying Albright on her world
 travel.
</P>
<P>
"Our objective was to see the unconditional return of the
 U.N. inspectors. Our strategy was to combine intensive
 diplomacy, that is the unity of the major powers, with a robust
 military posture and if the inspectors return, then our
 objectives will have been met," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
